[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ I am very excited to introduce the reader to the third and last part of my 1.e4 series!    I, Alexandru Banzea from Romania, have been a Fide Master since 2015 and an International Master since the early part of 2020. I am truly honored that we have gotten this far with the Repertoire and thankful for all the great feedback that I've been getting from both students, and Chessable staff.     My most notable results are the Gold Medal at the European Championship U18 with the Romanian Team where I was playing on the second board in Bad Blankenburg @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@, and the Bronze Medal at the Individual Rapid Championship U18 in Oradea in 2018. The year 2018 was very special to me because I also managed to win the Romanian Championship U18 in Classical, Rapid and Blitz time controls. When I became a Fide Master in 2015 at the age of 15, I started working with Constantin Lupulescu, one of the greatest Romanian players of all time and later on, one of my best friends. If there is someone who constantly helped and motivated me throughout the years to continue with my chess career, it’s him! He is the guy who deserves all the credits, and I will always be grateful to him for that.    I was born in the strong engines era, where having a deep preparation and understanding of the openings is more important than ever. I was 10 years old when I first used an engine, and I remember that Stockfish was gaining a lot of popularity back then, while engines such as IvanHoe and Rybka were also used. I never really used the Fritz engine, although I think it was not inferior to others at that time. The game-changer came in 2018, when Google introduced its AlphaZero @@StartBracket@@A0@@EndBracket@@, which demolished the top program Stockfish 8 with considerable ease. A0 uses a neural network to play the game of chess, which was a novelty in the world of chess engines. An open-source project, based on Google’s technique, started soon after, and nowadays Leela Zero @@StartBracket@@Lc0@@EndBracket@@ can be used by any chess fan across the globe. Although Lc0 has a very fine strategical understanding, Stockfish is much more precise when it comes to brute calculation; therefore, the perfect combo is to use both when analyzing - just as I did for this course!     The Vienna Opening/Gambit:  1.e4  e5  2.Nc3  Nc6  3.Bc4  / @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.f4  is the main keystone of the course. I really wanted to have a weapon that could be used in every game without fearing the fact that your opponent has prepared against it. I think that the Vienna is full of fresh positions with a lot of new ideas that you can be used to outplay your opponents. The volume of theory is quite high and looks pretty intimidating at first glance, but it covers all the small details and move orders that black can try. This chapter aims at helping you play the Vienna and to be a Lifetime Repertoire.   The Four Pawns Attack vs Alekhine Defense  1.e4  Nf6  2.e5  Nd5  3.c4  Nb6  4.d4  d6  5.f4  is mixing really well with the Austrian Attack against the Pirc @@StartBracket@@which I covered in the second part of the  1.e4  series@@EndBracket@@. Not only we get familiar positions, but we are also playing the most ambitious weapon against the Alekhine.   The Scandinavian  1.e4  d5  2.exd5  Qxd5  3.d4  : After playing exclusively  1.e4  for eleven years, I have tried almost everything against the Scandinavian. I have played both the aggressive main line with  3.Nc3  and the positional  3.Nf3  . However I decided to recommend the hidden idea of  3.d4!?  because I think it's a slightly improved version of  3.Nf3  , and it is quite simple to play. The problem with  3.Nc3  is that it involves a lot of knowledge and if you mess up the theory, you might get in trouble quite easily. Of course, if you learn the theory, the  3.Nc3  can be highly rewarding as well.  How to work with this course: I recommend abusing the move trainer technology with a big focus on the model games chapter, because that will really teach you how to play the middlegame phase, which is crucial for any successful player. Sometimes you might mess up the theory and get an equal position, but you can get an edge over your opponents by being the better player in the middlegame. As long as you are using the move trainer technology on a regular basis, you should have no issues remembering the lines, so it's all just about practice and patience until you see the results. }
