1. e4 e5
{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move from the most played move against 1.e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles.  Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot compared to the romantic period of chess when the old masters used to abuse the King's Gambit trying to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice, and most of the top players have switched to the more positional approach of going  2.Nf3  seeking to play The Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giouco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Despite the fact that those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames in order to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@ as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, played mainly as a surprise weapon at the very top level, but recently it got a nice boost mainly thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja.   The Vienna Game has the main perk that it avoids the Berlin Defence and the Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's main ways to kill the game before it begins!   I really want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is really easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two big alternatives despite the fact that I've also covered the sidelines.   Black's two main options are:   •2...Nf6 known as The Falkbeer Variation.   •2...Nc6 The Max Lange Defense. }
2... Nc6
{ The Max Lange Defense. Named after the Western German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against the Vienna Gambit because if White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  creating a very annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works really well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-...d5. Now White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3 then pushing f4 after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   This set-up is straightforward to play and quite effective since it's putting a lot of pressure both in the center and on the King-Side because White is always considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4. Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I really want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2...Nf6 because that would allow 3...Nxe4 ideas! This is really important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Bc5
{ Could be a tricky move order if you try to play in the 'normal' fashion with d3 and f4 because Black has ...Bxg1 and ...Qh4+ ideas due to the fact that he has not committed to playing...Nf6 yet. The good news is that White has a very strong way of dealing with this move order by playing the super concrete: }
4. Qg4
{ Simply highlighting the fact that the Bishop has been developed a little too early before playing ...Nf6! Black has a big choice now on how to defend against our threat: }
4... Qf6
{ Played over 20 000 times in online chess, but White is close to winning! } 5.
Nd5
{ Ignoring the ...Qxf2+ threat! The weakness of c7 combined with g7 is more important than a single pawn on f2. }
5... Qxf2+ 6. Kd1
{ Notice that the King is pretty safe on d1 while Black has two very annoying threats to deal with! }
6... Kf8 { Defending the Pg7 and sidestepping the fork. } 7. Nh3
{ Important to not go greedy, and start playing against the enemy Queen that is exposed! }
7... Qd4
{ Is the most popular choice for Black in online chess, but slightly inferior compared to 7...Ph5 }
8. d3 { Defending the Bishop and threatening to trap the enemy Queen with c3. }
8... Nf6
{ Is just leading to a lost position for Black after the straightforward: } 9.
Nxf6 gxf6 10. c3 { Forcing Qd6. } 10... Qd6 11. Bh6+ { Developing with tempo. }
11... Ke8 12. Qg7
{ With a massive lead in development for White who is most likely going to win at least an exchange soon. }
