{ The Max Lange Defense. Named after the Western German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against the Vienna Gambit because if White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  creating a very annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works really well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-...d5. Now White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3 then pushing f4 after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   This set-up is straightforward to play and quite effective since it's putting a lot of pressure both in the center and on the King-Side because White is always considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4. Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I really want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2...Nf6 because that would allow 3...Nxe4 ideas! This is really important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Na5
{ The mainline in OTB chess and also a popular choice for Black in online games.   Black can afford to move the Knight for the second time because there is no immediate way for White to punish it because the central situation is stable.   Now White has three main ways of playing this position, and I decided to recommend the least popular one of them: }
5. Qf3
{ Developing the Queen this early is not a common theme in Opening Theory, but in this particular line I found out that it works really well!  The point is that we are playing an improved version of the  5.Nge2  variation and the Queen proves to be very useful on the f3 square from where it supports an eventual Ng3-Nf5 maneuver, or when Black plays with the dark-squared Bishop outside of the pawn chain, White will have a very annoying  Bg5!?  idea, threatening to ruin the enemy pawn structure.  Overall Black should be able to get a solid set-up, but I find the upcoming positions much easier to play for White, and highly underrated. Also as an interesting fact, I found out that Wesley So used to abuse this line with White while he was making his entrance to the top-level chess a while ago, and he will be our model player in this pawn structure after Black takes on c4. }
5... Nxc4
{ The most straightforward continuation, and the main line in both OTB and online chess. }
6. dxc4
{ Now Black has a choice, the main question is what to do with the dark-squared Bishop? Most of the people prefer to keep it inside the pawn chain and play  6...Be7  or  6...d6  , but we will also cover the alternatives: }
6... d6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  but it's gonna end up being the same thing, so I decided to focus all the material on this particular move order.  This variation is the most popular for Black, and I want to explain why because I feel like a lot of people find it pretty strange that Black voluntarily plays with a closed dark-squared Bishop when he could simply pick one of the aforementioned lines have an active Bishop. One of the concrete reasons is that Black is no longer afraid of  Bg5  ideas by White because the Bishop on  e7  plays a great role in defending the  f6  Knight, but on the other hand, this line is more ambitious because it's keeping the Bishop Pair on the board and it gives Black outplay potential in the long run.  The good news is that if you know how to handle this structure and understand the main plans and concepts, Black will have a hard time finding any active resources while White can build up the pressure slowly but steadily without many risks. }
7. Nge2
{ As a rule of thumb, you should not be afraid of ...Bg4 because we can simply play Qd3 and kick the Bishop later with h3, this way winning half a tempo. We could also start by playing 7.h3 because it's a useful move in this structure, but why not give Black the temptation of playing an active but inferior move? }
7... Be7 { I decided to make this the main move order as it's preparing O-O. }
8. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4 ideas, and preparing g4 in some positions. } 8... O-O
9. b3 { Not rushing with O-O because Black is fine after the ...Nd7-Bg5 plan. }
9... Re8 10. O-O Bf8 11. Bg5 *

