{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move from the most played move against 1.e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles.  Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot compared to the romantic period of chess when the old masters used to abuse the King's Gambit trying to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice, and most of the top players have switched to the more positional approach of going  2.Nf3  seeking to play The Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giouco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Despite the fact that those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames in order to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@ as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite chessable author Anish Giri do. }
