[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move from the most played move against 1.e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles.  Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot compared to the romantic period of chess when the old masters used to abuse the King's Gambit trying to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice, and most of the top players have switched to the more positional approach of going  2.Nf3  seeking to play The Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giouco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Despite the fact that those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames in order to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@ as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, played mainly as a surprise weapon at the very top level, but recently it got a nice boost mainly thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja.   The Vienna Game has the main perk that it avoids the Berlin Defence and the Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's main ways to kill the game before it begins!   I really want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is really easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two big alternatives despite the fact that I've also covered the sidelines.   Black's two main options are:   •2...Nf6 known as The Falkbeer Variation.   •2...Nc6 The Max Lange Defense. }
2... Nc6
{ The Max Lange Defense. Named after the Western German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against the Vienna Gambit because if White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  creating a very annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works really well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-...d5. Now White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3 then pushing f4 after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   This set-up is straightforward to play and quite effective since it's putting a lot of pressure both in the center and on the King-Side because White is always considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4. Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I really want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2...Nf6 because that would allow 3...Nxe4 ideas! This is really important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Bb4
{ This is one of the most principled ways for Black to counter White's set-up. The point is to strike in the center with ...d5 on the next move. Objectively speaking, Black should be fine, but the positions are fresh and generally, White has more accessible play, at least in my humble opinion. As a side note, many people might play this variation trying to follow Sethuraman's 1...e5 Lifetime Repertoire so we need to be well prepared against it! }
5. Ne2 { Reinforcing the Nc3 and preparing O-O. } 5... d5
{ The best way to justify the presence of the Bb4! Black is able to strike in the center, trying to equalize on the spot. From my personal experience, whenever one of the sides manages to deliver a central pawn break like this one, it usually results in a very comfortable game, but I've been really surprised when I first found out about this line that White has a lot of tricky ideas to test his opponents! Objectively speaking, Black should be able to equalize with the best play, this particular variation being one of the main theoretical ways to play for Black, but I think it's definitely more fun to play with White. }
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Now we arrived at a critical point for the whole Vienna Game! I expect you to have a lot of games starting from this position, and it's important to understand the small nuances in order to get any real pressure, otherwise Black will get easy development without having too much to worry about. }
7... Nxc3
{ The main move in online chess, and relatively popular in OTB chess as well, with Alireza Firouzja and Markus Ragger among the best players to implement this. }
8. bxc3
{ The main move, used by Hikaru Nakamura and the majority of the top rated players of the White side. By recapturing with the pawn, White get's the doubled pawns, but in exchange for it White gets a lot of dynamic compensation because he can either use the b file for the Rook, or/and use the Knight on the King-Side after Ng3-Qh5 @@StartBracket@@this is a common idea that you will see later@@EndBracket@@. Last but not least, the pawn on c3 is controlling the key d4 square which could have been used by the enemy Nc6. Now Black can do pretty much anything with the Bishop, but our ideas generally remain the same as you will see in the following lines: }
8... Bd6
{ The most popular move in both online chess and OTB. The Bishop is well placed on d6 because it's guarding the Pe5 while also keeping control over the f4 square, in case White decides to push, Black will be able to trade a pair of minor pieces which is generally helping the defending side. }
9. Ng3
{ Generally I am not a huge fan of the Knight being on g3 because they are usually vulnerable to Ph5-Ph4 ideas, but in this particular case this plan works really well because the Queen can join the King-Side on the next move with Qh5, and also the Ng3 can potentially jump to e4 from where it's threatening to win the Bishop Pair. }
9... O-O 10. Qh5
{ The Queen is very annoying for Black on the King-Side, and we would be really pleased to see Black creating a weakness with ...Pg6 because we can safely play Qh6 and later try to use the enemy dark squares. Now White is threatening to play Ne4 next, and besides the Nxd6 idea to win the Bishop Pair, White will also be threatening the deadly Ng5! @@StartBracket@@this is a huge combo that you need to have in your toolkit because Black is unable to defend both f7 and h7 simultanously which gives you a win on the spot@@EndBracket@@. }
*

