{ The best way to justify the presence of the Bb4! Black is able to strike in the center, trying to equalize on the spot. From my personal experience, whenever one of the sides manages to deliver a central pawn break like this one, it usually results in a very comfortable game, but I've been really surprised when I first found out about this line that White has a lot of tricky ideas to test his opponents! Objectively speaking, Black should be able to equalize with the best play, this particular variation being one of the main theoretical ways to play for Black, but I think it's definitely more fun to play with White. }
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Now we arrived at a critical point for the whole Vienna Game! I expect you to have a lot of games starting from this position, and it's important to understand the small nuances in order to get any real pressure, otherwise Black will get easy development without having too much to worry about. }
7... Be6
{ The most principled and by far the most popular move for Black, and one of the main tabias of the Vienna Game! Here I want you to remember the following combo: }
8. Bxd5
{ If you read my courses you know how much I am against giving up the Bishop Pair if not needed, but White has a very cool plan: }
8... Bxd5 9. f4
{ This is the modern concept of playing the Vienna Game! Now Black has a choice: }
9... O-O
{ Is the most common move for Black, and what you are most likely to face in your own games. Here I suggest we step away from the most explored territory and go for: }
10. Nxd5
{ The plan remains the same as in the most common  10.f5  line: White wants to go for f5 and the Ng3-Ne4 combined with good play on the King-Side after Rf3-Rh3 with Qh5 looming. The big difference is that in the  10.f5  line, Black gets time to trade off the dark-squared Bishop with  10...Bxc3  , and I'd like to take that option away from him if possible because the dark-squared Bishop remains out of the game when we do our light-squared strategy with f5 and Ne4. }
10... Qxd5 11. f5
{ Threatening to push f6 next and deal damage to the enemy King. } 11... f6
{ Is the standard way to react for Black. } 12. Ng3
{ One of the main ideas behind White's set-up! The Knight is heading to the e4 square from where it can hardly be challenged. }
12... Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Rad8 14. Ne4
{ With an easy game for White who can continue with Bd2-Qg4 and then the Rook lift becomes really annoying for Black because once White gets in Rf3-Rh3 it will be hard to deal with the pressure over the h file. }
