{ The point of having played 3... d5! Black gets the e4-square for his Knight and solves the first problem. Black has some annoying ...Qh4+ ideas that we have to deal with now. The most natural way to block the check is to play the old main line with  5.Nf3  , but I am not a big fan of it because I feel like Black has plenty of ways to get a playable position. Therefore I recommend we try the more venomous and modern main line by playing: }
5. Qf3
{ Putting pressure on the e4-Knight and preparing to meet ...Qh4+ with g3! Of course, it looks a bit strange to develop the Queen this early in the game, but here we gain a tempo. Sometimes you have to do these things to get a new position with a lot of room to outplay your opponent @@StartBracket@@see the Harikrishna System from the Anti-Sicilian Toolkit@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nc6
{ This is an interesting idea meant to answer the most natural  6.Nxe4  with the strong  ...Nd4!  and Black has very good counterplay. The good news is that we can pin the c6-Knight and avoid the crazy lines by playing: }
6. Bb5
{ Pinning the potentially dangerous Knight and renewing the Nxe4 threat. Most of the time, Black decides to force an endgame by playing  6...Nxc3  followed by  7.--  Qh4+  with ...Qe4+ to come. On the other hand, I've noticed a considerable amount of ways to deviate for Black that have been tried in online chess, and I decided that it's worth adding them: }
6... Nxc3 { The main line of 5... Nc6!? } 7. dxc3 { Opening up the c1-Bishop. }
7... Qh4+
{ Going for the endgame is the ''easy way out'' for Black. The good news is that it could become tricky to keep the e4-pawn under protection. }
8. g3 Qe4+ 9. Qxe4 dxe4
{ In this position, a lot of people went for  10.Bxc6+  , but I feel like Black is getting a bit too much control over the light squares, so I suggest: }
10. Be3
{ The best square for the Bishop since we might use the f-file later for the Rook, as after Ne2, Rf1 becomes a thing. }
10... Bd7 { Threatening ...Nxe5! } 11. Bxc6
{ Now that the Bishop is on d7, it's much safer to go for this trade, because we can attack the bishop once it lands on c6 by playing Ne2-Nd4 in the future. }
11... Bxc6 12. Ne2
{ With Nd4 next, White keeps annoying pressure in the endgame. Just keep in mind that ...Bd5 becomes vulnerable to b3-c4 ideas and ...Bd7 can be met by Rf1-Rf4 ideas, and Black is having troubles defending the e4-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Vienna Gambit"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move, being the most played move against 1. e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles. Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot when compared to the romantic period of chess. The old masters abused the King's Gambit, attempting to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice.  Most of the current top players have switched to a more positional approach with 2. Nf3, seeking to play the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Although those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  , Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@, as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite Chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Nf6
{ The most common move in OTB chess by far, but a little bit less popular in online chess compared to  2...Nc6  . The big difference between these two seemingly similar-looking moves is that the  2...Nf6  variation gives Black an additional option to meet our ideal  3.Bc4  with  ...Nxe4  leading to some complications after the interesting  4.Qh5  move, where I believe Black should be fine.   The reason I skipped 3. Bc4, despite it being very playable, is that the arising positions might not suit everyone's taste, and I felt like a lot more people would be enjoying the Vienna Gambit. }
3. f4
{ The starting position for the Vienna Gambit, and already a critical moment for Black! What I love about this variation is that if Black doesn't play  3...d5  , he is much worse as early as move three! Besides that, we are in new territory and have unlimited room for analysis. }
3... d5 { Black's best reaction and the big main line. } 4. fxe5 Nxe4
{ The point of having played 3... d5! Black gets the e4-square for his Knight and solves the first problem. Black has some annoying ...Qh4+ ideas that we have to deal with now. The most natural way to block the check is to play the old main line with  5.Nf3  , but I am not a big fan of it because I feel like Black has plenty of ways to get a playable position. Therefore I recommend we try the more venomous and modern main line by playing: }
5. Qf3
{ Putting pressure on the e4-Knight and preparing to meet ...Qh4+ with g3! Of course, it looks a bit strange to develop the Queen this early in the game, but here we gain a tempo. Sometimes you have to do these things to get a new position with a lot of room to outplay your opponent @@StartBracket@@see the Harikrishna System from the Anti-Sicilian Toolkit@@EndBracket@@. }
5... f5
{ Recommended by both Gustafsson and Sethuraman in their Lifetime Repertoires! This is a very risky continuation, strategically speaking. The point is that it's connected with a very concrete approach, as White would otherwise get a much better position by default. }
6. d3 { Getting rid of the strong knight. } 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ Now we are threatening to push d4 and get a much better position thanks to the solid situation in the center and a much more active light-squared Bishop. Therefore Black has to go for: }
7... d4
{ Very important, we would otherwise play d4 with a much better position as explained above. }
8. Qg3
{ The main move, making it tough for Black to develop the dark-squared Bishop while preparing a sneaky Be2-Bh5 maneuver! Black has two major moves, one recommended by Jan Gustafsson, and the other move championed by Sethuraman. }
8... dxc3 { Recommended by Jan in his Lifetime Repertoire. } 9. Be2
{ Creating a sneaky Bh5 threat because g6 can be met by the powerful Bxg6+! Bishop sacrifice when White has a winning attack! }
9... Be6
{ Jan's recommendation, with the idea to meet the Bishop sacrifice by playing ...Bf7! }
10. Bf3
{ Now that Bh5 was no longer effective due to ...g6, we can activate our Bishop by putting pressure on the b7-pawn at the same time. }
10... Nc6 { Threatening to jump around with ...Nd4/Nb4! } 11. Bxc6+
{ Eliminating Black's active counterplay. } 11... bxc6 12. Ne2
{ Preparing O-O and at some point to regain the c3-pawn. } 12... Qd7
{ Jan stops in his course here, saying that there is a complex fight ahead where Black should be fine after pushing ...h6 and g5. He is right in his assessment, but this is exactly what we are looking for! A complex fight where we can outplay our opponent because we have a better understanding of the position. I invite you to dive a little bit deeper into some of the possible continuations, although in my opinion, if you make it till here, you should be just fine. }
13. O-O
{ We will win back the sacrificed pawn, and Black's pawn structure is a little messed up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Alekhine "]
[Black "Alekhine #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine Defense. Black tempts the White pawns to move forward and form a board pawn center, with plans to undermine and attack the White structure later.  @@HeaderStart@@History@@HeaderEnd@@ The opening is named after Alexander Alekhine, who introduced it in the 1921 Budapest tournament in games against Endre Steiner and Fritz Sämisch.  @@HeaderStart@@Top Level Reputation@@HeaderEnd@@ The Alekhine's Defense was more popular in the past. For instance, Fischer used it in two games against Boris Spassky in the World Chess Championship 1972, and Korchnoi also included the defense in his repertoire, leading to its respectable reputation.   Nowadays, the Alekhine's defense is not so common at the top level. De Firmian observes, 'The fashion could quickly change if some champion of the opening takes up the cause, as the results Black has obtained in practice are good.' While the opening's current highest-rated proponent is GM Vassily Ivanchuk, Lev Alburt played it at grandmaster-level almost exclusively during his career and was responsible for many contributions in both theory and practice.   Currently, grandmasters Shabalov and Minasian regularly use the opening, while Aronian, Adams, and Nakamura occasionally use it. Carlsen does not employ the opening frequently, but he has used it occasionally in competitive games. Most notably, he defeated the former World Chess Champion Topalov in Linares 2008, employing the Alekhine's defense. }
2. e5
{ The most ambitious approach, accepting the challenge, we are going to build a massive pawn center. Before we dive into the main line theory, I want to quickly mention that as Vienna players, we have the option of playing  2.Nc3  , which couldtranspose to the Vienna if Black plays  2...e5  . But there are some lines you need to study if Black wants to deviate by going  2...d5  . }
2... Nd5 3. c4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ Attacking the d5-Knight, forcing it to b6. Another alternative is to play  2.d4  d6  . The big main line is now to go  3.Nf3  with a lot of theory and small nuances that you need to understand to get anything. I played that a couple of times, but it feels to me that it requires a bit too much effort for such a rare opening where the Black players generally know it well, and it could get pretty annoying to dive into their preparation. }
3... Nb6 4. d4
{ Setting up a strong pawn center. If you are looking for a fancy line,  4.a4  a5  5.Ra3  ➼ heading towards the g3-square could give you a fun game, but it's also double-edged. }
4... d6
{ The only move to not get a losing position on the spot! Black is threatening to play ...dxe5, heading towards a much better endgame because our e5-pawn will be a bit overextended. Of course, we are not allowing such things, and we will play  5.f4!  going for the most principled and aggressive continuation.  •  5.exd6  is another playable line for White, but leading to more balanced positions. }
5. f4
{ The most ambitious approach, and generally what your opponent hates to see! The point is that we can answer  5...dxe5  with  6.fxe5!  , avoiding the potential Queen trade on the d-file, and White manages to keep a strong center.   Now Black can choose between a variety of moves:  •  5...dxe5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... g6
{ This is an interesting variation for Black, but White gets a nice position if he is well prepared. At first, it doesn't seem logical for Black to place his Bishop on g7 when we have such a strong pawn on e5, but the idea is to undermine White's center later with ...c5! }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3
{ The best square for the Bishop. In case Black goes for the natural  7...O-O  White gets a strong initiative after  8.c5! }
7... Be6
{ This finesse is Black's main trick, and we are covering it in the main part of the course. }
*

