{ The only move to not get a losing position on the spot! Black is threatening to play ...dxe5, heading towards a much better endgame because our e5-pawn will be a bit overextended. Of course, we are not allowing such things, and we will play  5.f4!  going for the most principled and aggressive continuation.  •  5.exd6  is another playable line for White, but leading to more balanced positions. }
5. f4
{ The most ambitious approach, and generally what your opponent hates to see! The point is that we can answer  5...dxe5  with  6.fxe5!  , avoiding the potential Queen trade on the d-file, and White manages to keep a strong center.   Now Black can choose between a variety of moves:  •  5...dxe5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... dxe5 { This is by far the most played move in both OTB and online chess. }
6. fxe5 Nc6 { Developing the knight and putting pressure on the d4-pawn. } 7.
Be3
{ This move is important because it's the only way to defend the d4-pawn properly.  7.Nf3  would have allowed the oldest trick in the book with  ...Bg4  ,  and Black gets the dream scenario where he has good play against our pawns. Keep in mind that once we see Black commit with ...Bf5, then it's a good time to play Nf3 because he would have to waste a precious tempo to pin our Knight. }
7... Bf5
{ The main move for Black, with the idea to play ...e6 next without locking the light-squared Bishop. }
8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 { The main tabia of the line. Black has a big choice: } 9...
Qd7
{ This move couldtranspose to  9...Bg4  , but there is a way for Black to deviate from that line: }
10. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 10... O-O-O 11. O-O f6
{ This is the move that has some independent value. Black is trying to undermine White's center directly, and it's important to know how to counter this plan. Black could otherwise get a lot of counterplay.   11...Bg4  Transposing to 9... Bg4 and 11... O-O-O }
12. d5 { The most energetic continuation! } 12... exd5
{ Allows white to keep his center: } 13. Bxb6
{ After this strong intermezzo, Black is in trouble. } 13... axb6 14. cxd5
{ And Black is in trouble because ...Nxe5 is not working in view of Nxe5 followed by Rxf5! and White wins a piece because there is Bg4 at the end of the line. }
