1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine Defense. Black tempts the White pawns to move forward and form a board pawn center, with plans to undermine and attack the White structure later.  @@HeaderStart@@History@@HeaderEnd@@ The opening is named after Alexander Alekhine, who introduced it in the 1921 Budapest tournament in games against Endre Steiner and Fritz Sämisch.  @@HeaderStart@@Top Level Reputation@@HeaderEnd@@ The Alekhine's Defense was more popular in the past. For instance, Fischer used it in two games against Boris Spassky in the World Chess Championship 1972, and Korchnoi also included the defense in his repertoire, leading to its respectable reputation.   Nowadays, the Alekhine's defense is not so common at the top level. De Firmian observes, 'The fashion could quickly change if some champion of the opening takes up the cause, as the results Black has obtained in practice are good.' While the opening's current highest-rated proponent is GM Vassily Ivanchuk, Lev Alburt played it at grandmaster-level almost exclusively during his career and was responsible for many contributions in both theory and practice.   Currently, grandmasters Shabalov and Minasian regularly use the opening, while Aronian, Adams, and Nakamura occasionally use it. Carlsen does not employ the opening frequently, but he has used it occasionally in competitive games. Most notably, he defeated the former World Chess Champion Topalov in Linares 2008, employing the Alekhine's defense. }
2. e5
{ The most ambitious approach, accepting the challenge, we are going to build a massive pawn center. Before we dive into the main line theory, I want to quickly mention that as Vienna players, we have the option of playing  2.Nc3  , which couldtranspose to the Vienna if Black plays  2...e5  . But there are some lines you need to study if Black wants to deviate by going  2...d5  . }
2... Nd5 3. c4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ Attacking the d5-Knight, forcing it to b6. Another alternative is to play  2.d4  d6  . The big main line is now to go  3.Nf3  with a lot of theory and small nuances that you need to understand to get anything. I played that a couple of times, but it feels to me that it requires a bit too much effort for such a rare opening where the Black players generally know it well, and it could get pretty annoying to dive into their preparation. }
3... Nb6 4. d4
{ Setting up a strong pawn center. If you are looking for a fancy line,  4.a4  a5  5.Ra3  ➼ heading towards the g3-square could give you a fun game, but it's also double-edged. }
4... d6
{ The only move to not get a losing position on the spot! Black is threatening to play ...dxe5, heading towards a much better endgame because our e5-pawn will be a bit overextended. Of course, we are not allowing such things, and we will play  5.f4!  going for the most principled and aggressive continuation.  •  5.exd6  is another playable line for White, but leading to more balanced positions. }
5. f4
{ The most ambitious approach, and generally what your opponent hates to see! The point is that we can answer  5...dxe5  with  6.fxe5!  , avoiding the potential Queen trade on the d-file, and White manages to keep a strong center.   Now Black can choose between a variety of moves:  •  5...dxe5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... Bf5
{ This variation couldtranspose to the main line with  5...dxe5  and 7... Bf5, but it does have some independent value if Black decides to postpone the move ...Nc6 }
6. Nc3 e6 7. Nf3 dxe5 8. fxe5
{ Now Black has a variety of ways to deviate from the most popular  8...Nc6  move, which istransposing back to the main lines with 5... dxe5 and 7... Bf5. The alternatives are:   •  8...Be7   •  8...Bg4   •  8...Bb4 }
8... Be7 { Preparing ...O-O. } 9. Be3
{ The best square for the dark-squared Bishop, keeping the d4-pawn very solid. }
9... O-O 10. Be2
{ Preparing O-O. Now Black cantranspose to the main line by playing  10...Nc6  , but we are going to focus on what happens if Black tries to undermine our center: }
10... f6 11. exf6
{ 11.O-O  Would lead to the same thing, transposing to our line after  11...Nc6  12.exf6  Bxf6 }
11... Bxf6 12. O-O Nc6 13. b3
{ Defending the c4-pawn and preparing to play Bd3. Keep in mind that if Black tries to eliminate the f3-Knight with ...Bg4, it allows us to jump with the Knight on e4 ➼ eliminating the enemy dark-squared Bishop! }
13... Qe7 14. Bd3
{ The best move made by Xiong, improving over his previous game against Duda that went  14.Qe1  Rad8  with a complicated game. }
14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3
{ We are going to play Rae1 on the next move with pressure on the e6-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter: The Scandinavian"]
[Black "Scandinavian #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ @@HeaderStart@@Origin@@HeaderEnd@@ The Scandinavian Defense is one of the oldest recorded openings, first recorded as being played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475 in what may be the first recorded game of modern chess, and being mentioned by Lucena in 1497.  @@HeaderStart@@19th and early 20th centuries@@HeaderEnd@@ Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century showed it is playable for Black. Ludvig Collijn played the opening with success. Although the Scandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, Joseph Henry Blackburne and Jacques Mieses often played it, developing its theory in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. It was an occasional choice in this era for top players including Siegbert Tarrasch, Rudolph Spielmann, and Savielly Tartakower. Alexander Alekhine used it to draw against World Champion Emanuel Lasker at St. Petersburg 1914, and future World Champion José Raúl Capablanca won twice with it at New York 1915.  @@HeaderStart@@Modern era@@HeaderEnd@@ Danish Grandmaster Bent Larsen, a four-time world championship candidate, played it occasionally from the 1960s onwards. He defeated World Champion Anatoly Karpov with it at Montreal 1979, spurring a rise in popularity. Around this time, the popular name also began to switch from 'Center Counter Defense' to 'Scandinavian Defense.' Danish GM Curt Hansen is also considered an expert in the opening. Australian GM Ian Rogers has adopted it frequently starting in the 1980s.   In 1995, the Scandinavian Defense made its first appearance in a world chess championship match, in the 14th game of the PCA final at New York City. Viswanathan Anand obtained an excellent position with the opening, playing with the Black pieces against Garry Kasparov, although Kasparov won the game. During the sixth round of the 2014 Chess Olympiad at Tromsø, Magnus Carlsen chose the Scandinavian against Fabiano Caruana and won. Carlsen used the opening again to draw with Caruana at the 2016 Chess Olympiad at Baku.  @@HeaderStart@@Nowadays experts@@HeaderEnd@@ The biggest experts for the Black side of the Scandinavian that are implementing it regularly in their tournament practice in our time are:  - Grandmaster Sergey Tiviakov from the Netherlands @@StartBracket@@not only did he play the opening a lot, but he also wrote many articles about it, developing the theory@@EndBracket@@.  - Grandmaster Igor Kovalenko from Latvia. }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ The Modern Variation, tempting white to keep the extra pawn with c4. } 3. d4
{ The best move, playing for a healthy position. When I first encountered this variation in my tournament practice eleven years ago @@StartBracket@@I was ten years old at the time@@EndBracket@@, I went greedy with  3.c4  and soon started to regret it after my opponent played  ...c6  and got a nice gambit. Despite not having the game in the database, I have it written in my memory as if it was played yesterday because I was truly impressed by Black's compensation.   Long story short, I got introduced to the theory after analyzing the game with my coach. He advised me to stay ''humble'' and focus on development with  3.d4!  That was a precious lesson at that time, and I have to say that it served me very well in the last decade! }
3... Nxd5
{ The Marshall Variation. My general feeling against this opening is that White gets a much better position after kicking the Knight with  4.c4  . After the most natural  4...Nb6  White gets a nice initiative based on  5.c5!  ,  and then Bc4 and Nc3 with a lot of pressure in the center.   The only difference is if Black plays  4.c4  Bf5  , when  5.Bd3!  is strong, avoiding the ...Nb4 tricks. }
4. Nf3
{ Now Black has a choice between three main options:  •  4...g6   •  4...Bg4   •  4...Bf5 }
4... Bg4
{ By far the most common move in online chess, and very popular in OTB as well. Black is planning to finish development by playing ...e6 and Be7, followed by ...O-O without locking the light-squared Bishop inside the pawn chain. }
5. c4 { The key reaction. White wins a lot of tempi by using this pawn push. }
5... Nb6 6. c5
{ Very committal and strong! When I first came across this idea, strategically speaking, it looked a bit risky because we are giving Black the d5-square. The point is that White is too fast with Bc4, Nc3, and Qb3 ideas, and Black can't make good use of the d5-square. }
6... Nd5 7. Qb3
{ All of a sudden, Black has problems with the b7-pawn because ...Qc8 drops the d5-Knight. }
7... Bxf3 { Fails to the very concrete: } 8. Qxb7
{ Hitting the a8-Rook first, and then we can collect the f3-Bishop. } 8... Nd7
9. gxf3 e6 10. Nc3 { Threatening Nxd5. } 10... Rb8 11. Qxa7
{ White can come back with the Queen via a6-e2 with a winning position. } *

