1. e4 d5
{ @@HeaderStart@@Origin@@HeaderEnd@@ The Scandinavian Defense is one of the oldest recorded openings, first recorded as being played between Francesc de Castellví and Narcís Vinyoles in Valencia in 1475 in what may be the first recorded game of modern chess, and being mentioned by Lucena in 1497.  @@HeaderStart@@19th and early 20th centuries@@HeaderEnd@@ Analysis by Scandinavian masters in the late 19th century showed it is playable for Black. Ludvig Collijn played the opening with success. Although the Scandinavian Defense has never enjoyed widespread popularity among top-flight players, Joseph Henry Blackburne and Jacques Mieses often played it, developing its theory in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. It was an occasional choice in this era for top players including Siegbert Tarrasch, Rudolph Spielmann, and Savielly Tartakower. Alexander Alekhine used it to draw against World Champion Emanuel Lasker at St. Petersburg 1914, and future World Champion José Raúl Capablanca won twice with it at New York 1915.  @@HeaderStart@@Modern era@@HeaderEnd@@ Danish Grandmaster Bent Larsen, a four-time world championship candidate, played it occasionally from the 1960s onwards. He defeated World Champion Anatoly Karpov with it at Montreal 1979, spurring a rise in popularity. Around this time, the popular name also began to switch from 'Center Counter Defense' to 'Scandinavian Defense.' Danish GM Curt Hansen is also considered an expert in the opening. Australian GM Ian Rogers has adopted it frequently starting in the 1980s.   In 1995, the Scandinavian Defense made its first appearance in a world chess championship match, in the 14th game of the PCA final at New York City. Viswanathan Anand obtained an excellent position with the opening, playing with the Black pieces against Garry Kasparov, although Kasparov won the game. During the sixth round of the 2014 Chess Olympiad at Tromsø, Magnus Carlsen chose the Scandinavian against Fabiano Caruana and won. Carlsen used the opening again to draw with Caruana at the 2016 Chess Olympiad at Baku.  @@HeaderStart@@Nowadays experts@@HeaderEnd@@ The biggest experts for the Black side of the Scandinavian that are implementing it regularly in their tournament practice in our time are:  - Grandmaster Sergey Tiviakov from the Netherlands @@StartBracket@@not only did he play the opening a lot, but he also wrote many articles about it, developing the theory@@EndBracket@@.  - Grandmaster Igor Kovalenko from Latvia. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ The Mieses-Kotroc Variation. This is the most popular move among the Black players when going for the Scandinavian Defense. Everyone plays the automatic  3.Nc3  move in this position, attacking the early developed Queen and then stepping into the center with d4. Despite the objective value of 3. Nc3, it requires a lot of knowledge in a variety of lines because Black has three viable options:   •  3...Qa5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  3...Qd6  @@StartBracket@@The Gubinsky-Melts Defense, developed by Sergey Tiviakov@@EndBracket@@  •  3...Qd8  @@StartBracket@@with the idea to play ...Nf6-g6-Bg7@@EndBracket@@ is also fashionable nowadays.   Another playable variation for White is the  3. Nf3-line, which is a pretty standard way to avoid the crazy theoretical lines while keeping a small positional edge. This variation is quite similar to my recommendation, but the main drawback of the line is that Black can force a balanced endgame after the precise  3...Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  . Now it's nice for White to include  5.h3  , and Black's best option is to go for  ...Bxf3!  6.Bxf3  . The big point is to play  ...Qe6+!  now, when White has nothing better than to trade Queens with  7.Qe2  . Black is very active in exchange for the Bishop pair. Now that you have a decent overview of White's choices, I think we can move on to my recommendation: }
3. d4
{ The point of this move is to play c4 followed by Nc3, avoiding one of the main issues that White has in the  3.Nc3  main lines. ➼ The d4-pawn can become vulnerable if White does not play the opening properly. Most of the time, we will transpose into the  3.Nf3  lines in a way where we avoid the aforementioned endgame! Of course, Black has some ways to deviate from the transposition, but we are going to analyze all of them in great depth. }
3... e5
{ This is one of the critical alternatives that Black gets against our 3. d4 line. The idea is to stop White from getting the ideal c4 and Nc3 while heading for a symmetrical pawn structure, which generally kills the game on the spot. The good news is that the following positions are tricky to play for Black, and White's advantage can easily start snowballing without much risk. It's important to remember the starting move: }
4. Nc3 { Temporarily sacrificing a pawn. } 4... Bb4
{ Pinning the c3-knight, played by Tiviakov. } 5. Ne2
{ Preparing to recapture on c3 with the knight! Now white is threatening to play a3 with a big initiative. }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4 { Going for a pleasant endgame. } 6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6
{ And now it's important to go for the concrete: } 8. Nb5
{ Forcing Black's Knight to a passive square. } 8... Na6 9. Bf4
{ Improving on Tiviakov's game that went  9.Be3  and Black later managed to outplay his opponent. }
9... c6 { Would be the ideal scenario for White! } 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6
{ And despite the symmetrical pawn structure, White is almost winning because Black is struggling to make a move. White can continue with castling long, Bxa6 followed by Rhe1 with a big advantage. }
*

