2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Bc5
{ The Anderssen Defense. This is most likely going to transpose into our main lines with 4... Bc5, but I found out that Black can also delay the move ...Nc6 for a bit. So it's important to be aware of it and not get shocked thinking that it's just a transposition when sometimes it's not! }
3. f4
{ I find this to be the most accurate move order. You could also start by playing  3.Bc4  , but by starting with  3.f4  we are putting more pressure over the center while setting up a trap. I've noticed that a lot of people find  3...Bxg1?  appealing both in online and OTB chess. }
3... d6 { The most common move. } 4. Nf3
{ Putting pressure in the center while preparing the standard play with Bc4 d3, and then Qe2 Be3 so that White will be able to castle short. }
4... Nf6 { Black's most common way of playing. } 5. Bc4
{ We are simply sticking to our guns, offering Black the chance totranspose back to the 4... Bc5 mainlines if he goes for ...Nc6. }
5... c6
{ This is one of the perks of delaying the move ...Nc6! Black can try to strike in the center with ...d5 next if White does not react properly. }
6. fxe5 { Eliminating any potential ...d5 ideas! } 6... dxe5 7. a3
{ Creating a square for the Bishop on a2 in case Black decides to expand on the Queenside with ...b5 and ...a5! }
7... O-O 8. d3
{ Preparing to go for the standard Qe2 and Be3 followed by O-O with pressure on the f-file. }
8... Nbd7 9. Qe2
{ Preparing to play Be3, making it possible to castle short next. } 9... b5 10.
Ba2 a5 11. Be3
{ With a pleasant position for White, who is ready to castle short next and play on the f-file. I want you to be aware of the following tactic if Black goes too crazy on the Queenside: }
11... b4
{ Looks a bit annoying at first, but I want you to know that playing the casual Nd1 is also completely fine for White here. We can exploit Black with a surprising but also a rather typical tactic: }
12. Bxc5 Nxc5 13. axb4 { Opening up the a-file, setting up a trap: } 13... axb4
14. Bxf7+
{ This is a nice motif that you should be familiar with. While more common for the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@, but I think that knowing this general idea helps you a lot to improve as a player. }
14... Rxf7 15. Rxa8 { The point. White collects the undefended Rook. } 15...
bxc3 16. bxc3
{ With an interesting material balance. Generally, this could get pretty double-edged, but in our case, White is better because Black is having no good squares for his minor pieces while White can also play for the weak pawns on c6 and e5. }
