{ Is another logical move for Black, preparing to strike in the center with ...d5 }
8. g4 { We are going to stick with the same novel idea proposed by Leela! }
8... Nxg4 9. Bg5
{ Remember that this is important to include once Black goes ...Nxg4. White wins an important tempo which is speeding up the process of castling long. }
9... Nf6
{ I don't see a lot of people pinning themselves like this, but it's fair to mention that White will continue with: }
10. Qd2 { Preparing O-O-O. } 10... Nbd7 11. O-O-O b5
{ Black starts his play on the Queenside. The good news is that this is not particularly threatening because Black does not have many pieces on the Queenside. Remember that the attack is generally successful when there are more attackers than defenders, which is not the case for Black here. }
12. Bb3 a5 { Threatening to trap our Bishop with ...a4 } 13. a4
{ And all of a sudden Black's play is no longer obvious, while White is ready to focus on the Kingside. }
13... b4 14. Ne2
{ With nice play for White on the Kingside based on Ng3-Nh5 and Qg2-Qh3 ideas. }
