{ The Anderssen Defense. This is most likely going to transpose into our main lines with 4... Bc5, but I found out that Black can also delay the move ...Nc6 for a bit. So it's important to be aware of it and not get shocked thinking that it's just a transposition when sometimes it's not! }
3. f4
{ I find this to be the most accurate move order. You could also start by playing  3.Bc4  , but by starting with  3.f4  we are putting more pressure over the center while setting up a trap. I've noticed that a lot of people find  3...Bxg1?  appealing both in online and OTB chess. }
3... d6 { The most common move. } 4. Nf3
{ Putting pressure in the center while preparing the standard play with Bc4 d3, and then Qe2 Be3 so that White will be able to castle short. }
4... Nf6 { Black's most common way of playing. } 5. Bc4
{ We are simply sticking to our guns, offering Black the chance to transpose back to the 4... Bc5 mainlines if he goes for ...Nc6. }
5... O-O 6. d3
{ Preparing to play Qe2 and Be3 if Black does nothing. Also, do not forget about the Na4 ideas that White can use if Black allows it. }
6... a6
{ Creating a square for the dark-squared Bishop on a7 while also preparing to expand on the Queenside with ...b5. }
7. f5
{ Very committal, but White gets a powerful initiative once g4 is played! }
7... c6
{ Is another logical move for Black, preparing to strike in the center with ...d5 }
8. g4 { We are going to stick with the same novel idea proposed by Leela! }
8... Nxg4 9. Bg5
{ Remember that this is important to include once Black goes ...Nxg4. White wins an important tempo which is speeding up the process of castling long. }
9... Qb6 { Hitting the b2-pawn. } 10. Bb3 { Simply defending against ...Qxb2 }
10... Nf2
{ This move can look terrifying at first, but Leela has a very subtle feeling for White's attacking chances on the Kingside: }
11. Qd2 { Simply sacrificing the full Rook! } 11... Nxh1 12. O-O-O
{ Threatening to collect the Knight. } 12... Nf2 13. Na4
{ Threatening to eliminate Black's dark-squared Bishop after which the f2-Knight will become vulnerable. }
13... Qc7 14. Nxc5
{ Giving up another exchange because we can go all-in for the attack: } 14...
Nxd1 15. Bh6
{ Threatening Qg5. Also, notice that the Bishop is untouchable on h6 because White will play Qxh6 followed by Ng5 with a typical mating construction. }
15... d5
{ This is a good try! Black is blocking our b3-Bishop, and now he is threatening to play ...f6 after which his Queen will join the defense! }
16. f6
{ Simply stopping Black from playing ...f6 and reinforcing the Qg5 threat. }
16... g6 { Only move. } 17. Bxf8
{ Collecting the Rook so that the Queen can come to h6. } 17... Kxf8 18. Qh6+
{ The Queen is powerful, especially because Black has no defenders near his King! }
18... Ke8 19. Qxh7
{ With a big initiative for White. Keep in mind that you have this lifeline with Kxd1, getting some of the sacrificed material back, while you can also look for a direct mating attack with Qg8+ and Qxf7+ }
