{ The main move, used by Hikaru Nakamura and the majority of the top-rated players for the White side. By recapturing with the pawn, White gets the doubled pawns but gets a lot of dynamic compensation in exchange for it because he can either use the b-file for the Rook or/and use the Knight on the Kingside after Ng3-Qh5 @@StartBracket@@this is a common idea that you will see later@@EndBracket@@.   Last but not least, the c3-pawn controls the d4-square and prevents the enemy Knight from using it. Now Black can do pretty much anything with the Bishop, but our ideas generally remain the same as you will see in the following lines: }
8... Ba5 { Is a bit of an odd square for the Bishop. } 9. Ba3
{ Keeping Black's King in the center. } 9... Qf6 10. Rb1
{ Notice that the Rook could be used via b5 in a lot of lines! } 10... Bb6 11.
Kh1
{ Unpinning so that we can go for f4 next, opening up the position to play against the enemy uncastled King. }
11... Be6 12. f4
