8. Bb3
{ In this position, Black tried three main ways of playing. Castling short is the most common, but we are also going to cover a few alternatives: }
8... Bg4
{ Pinning the Knight is usually a good idea, but in this case, with the King still in the center, White can get a quick initiative after: }
9. h3 { Forcing Black to choose a path. } 9... Bh5 10. f4
{ The typical pawn break! Now White is also threatening to play the direct g4 with the idea to trap the enemy Bishop next with f5. }
10... exf4 11. Qe1 { Unpinning with tempo! } 11... O-O 12. Nxf4 Bg6 13. Nxg6
{ Eliminating Black's light-squared Bishop so that we can press on the f7-pawn! }
13... hxg6 14. Qf2
{ With really annoying pressure on the f7-pawn and an unpleasant Ne4 incoming. }
