2... Nc6
{ The Max Lange Defense, named after the West German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against theVienna Gambit. If White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  ,  creating an annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. If we compare this with the Falkbeer Variation, it's easy to notice that 3. f4 becomes viable because the presence of the f6-Knight blocks the Queen from reaching h4 as in the other line. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-d5. White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3, then pushing f4, after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   Not only is this set-up easy to play, but it is also quite effective. It puts a lot of pressure on both the center and the Kingside because White is considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4.   Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2... Nf6 because that would allow 3... Nxe4 ideas! This is important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Bb4
{ This is one of the most principled ways for Black to counter White's set-up. The point is to strike in the center with ...d5 on the next move. Objectively speaking, Black should be fine, but the positions are fresh, and generally, White has easier play, at least in my humble opinion. As a side note, a lot of people might play this variation trying to follow Sethuraman's 1... e5 Lifetime Repertoire, so we need to be well prepared against it! }
5. Ne2 { Reinforcing the c3-Knight and preparing O-O. } 5... d5
{ The best way to justify the presence of the b4-Bishop! Black can strike in the center, trying to equalize on the spot. From my personal experience, whenever one of the sides delivers a central pawn break like this one, it usually results in a very comfortable game.   I was surprised when I first found out that White has many tricky ideas to test his opponents within this line! Objectively speaking, Black should be able to equalize with the best play, this particular variation being one of the main theoretical ways to play for Black, but I think it's more fun to play with White. }
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Now we arrived at a critical point for the whole Vienna Game! I expect you to have a lot of games starting from this position, and it's important to understand the small nuances to get any real pressure. Otherwise, Black will get easy development without having too much to worry about. }
7... Bxc3
{ This move was played by a surprising number of titled players, but I see no reason to give up the Bishop for free. }
8. Nxc3
{ Taking this way now because we are putting pressure on the enemy d5-Knight. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3np3/1bB5/2NP4/PPP1NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@Notice that in the  7...Nxc3  line we also recaptured with the pawn because  8.bxc3  was coming with tempo, hitting the Bishop on b4! }
8... Be6
{ Is rarely played in comparison to the  8...Nxc3  alternative. But still, I don't think that White has ever tried the best move. Here I suggest we go for: }
9. Qf3
{ This is my small improvement over what was tried so far. White is putting a lot of pressure on the enemy Knight on d5. Here Black either allows us to double his pawns, or he can enter the complications after  9...Nd4!? }
9... Nxc3 { Allows the intermediate: } 10. Bxe6 { Threatening mate on f7. }
10... fxe6 11. bxc3
{ With a small but stable edge for White thanks to the better pawn structure and the Bishop against Knight scenario. }
*

