{ Could be a way for Black to deviate from the main lines, but very rare. } 7.
Ba2
{ And suddenly Black has to be very precise and immediately strike in the center. Otherwise, Bg5 gives White a big edge. }
7... d5 { Threatening ...d4! } 8. Bd2
{ Breaking the pin and inviting Black to a reversed King's Indian structure. }
8... d4 9. Nb1
{ There is no shame in going back! The Knight might reach the c4-square one day, from where it's actively putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
9... Qe7 10. h3 { Avoiding any ...Bg4 ideas. } 10... O-O 11. Qd1
{ The Queen has to stay away from the f-pawn! White is preparing to play Ne2! and O-O, followed by the typical f4-break. }
11... Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 c5
{ Played to get the Knight back in the game at some point. } 13. Ne2
{ Really important! You don't want to play the supernatural Nf3 because that move will block your main pawn break! }
13... Be6 14. O-O
{ 14.Bxe6  seems natural, but Black can play:  14...fxe6∞  And our Knight lacks good squares. The position is around equal, of course. }
14... Nd7 15. f4 { With the typical play on the Kingside. } *

