2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Nc6
{ The Max Lange Defense, named after the West German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against theVienna Gambit. If White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  ,  creating an annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. If we compare this with the Falkbeer Variation, it's easy to notice that 3. f4 becomes viable because the presence of the f6-Knight blocks the Queen from reaching h4 as in the other line. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-d5. White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3, then pushing f4, after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   Not only is this set-up easy to play, but it is also quite effective. It puts a lot of pressure on both the center and the Kingside because White is considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4.   Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2... Nf6 because that would allow 3... Nxe4 ideas! This is important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Na5
{ The main line in OTB chess and also a popular choice for Black in online games. Black can afford to move the Knight for the second time because White has no immediate way to punish it. After all, the central situation is stable. Now White has three main ways of playing this position, and I decided to recommend the least popular one of them: }
5. Qf3
{ Developing the Queen this early is not a common theme in Opening Theory, but in this particular line, I found out that it works well! The point is that we are playing an improved version of the  5.Nge2  variation. The Queen proves to be very useful on the f3-square from where it supports an eventual Ng3-Nf5 maneuver, or when Black plays with the dark-squared Bishop outside the pawn chain, White will have a very annoying Bg5!? idea, threatening to ruin the enemy pawn structure. Black should be able to get a solid set-up, but I find the upcoming positions much easier to play for White and highly underrated.   Also, as an interesting fact, I found out that Wesley So used to abuse this line with White while he was making his entrance to the top-level chess a while ago, and he will be our model player in this pawn structure after Black takes on c4. }
5... Nxc4
{ The most straightforward continuation, and the main line in both OTB and online chess. }
6. dxc4
{ Now Black has a choice, the main question is what to do with the dark-squared Bishop? Most people prefer to keep it inside the pawn chain and play  6...Be7  or  6...d6  , but we will also cover the alternatives: }
6... Bb4
{ Is a playable line for Black, but the problem is that White can harass the Bishop on b4 and eventually trade it, this way getting rid of the Bishop pair. }
7. Ne2 d6 8. O-O
{ You can also start with h3 if you want to avoid ...Bg4 ideas, but it's generally not doing much for Black. }
8... Bg4
{ The Bishop is pretty active for the moment, but we will kick it back with h3 soon. }
9. Qd3 O-O 10. h3 Be6
{ And now what happened is that White has got h3 and the Queen on d3 instead of f3, which I think should be in our favor, but the position remains very solid for both sides. }
11. b3 { A nice small move to overprotect the c4-pawn. } 11... Nd7 12. Ng3
{ The Knight is heading to f5 in some positions. } 12... Nc5 13. Qf3
{ Threatening to play Nd5 and the Bishop remains quite loose on b4. Black has to do something concrete: }
13... Bxc3 { The Bishop might otherwise remain out of the game. } 14. Qxc3 f5
{ White would otherwise slowly build up the pressure with Be3 and the standard small but steady pressure. }
15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nxf5
{ Taking the Bishop is already a small strategical victory for White. } 16...
Rxf5 17. Be3 { Threatening to ruin the enemy pawn structure with Bxc5. } 17...
Ne6 18. Rad1
{ With a typical initiative on the Queenside for the King's Indian structure with b4 and c5, while Black does not have as much to do on the Kingside as he would like. }
