3... Nf6 4. d3 Na5
{ The main line in OTB chess and also a popular choice for Black in online games. Black can afford to move the Knight for the second time because White has no immediate way to punish it. After all, the central situation is stable. Now White has three main ways of playing this position, and I decided to recommend the least popular one of them: }
5. Qf3
{ Developing the Queen this early is not a common theme in Opening Theory, but in this particular line, I found out that it works well! The point is that we are playing an improved version of the  5.Nge2  variation. The Queen proves to be very useful on the f3-square from where it supports an eventual Ng3-Nf5 maneuver, or when Black plays with the dark-squared Bishop outside the pawn chain, White will have a very annoying Bg5!? idea, threatening to ruin the enemy pawn structure. Black should be able to get a solid set-up, but I find the upcoming positions much easier to play for White and highly underrated.   Also, as an interesting fact, I found out that Wesley So used to abuse this line with White while he was making his entrance to the top-level chess a while ago, and he will be our model player in this pawn structure after Black takes on c4. }
5... Nxc4
{ The most straightforward continuation, and the main line in both OTB and online chess. }
6. dxc4
{ Now Black has a choice, the main question is what to do with the dark-squared Bishop? Most people prefer to keep it inside the pawn chain and play  6...Be7  or  6...d6  , but we will also cover the alternatives: }
6... d6
{ Black can also start with  6...Be7  ,  but it's going to end up being the same thing, so I decided to focus all the material on this particular move order. This is the most popular variation for Black, and I want to explain why because I feel like many people find it strange that Black voluntarily plays with a closed dark-squared Bishop. Especially when he could pick one of the previously mentioned lines and have an active Bishop.   One of the concrete reasons is that Black is no longer afraid of Bg5 ideas by White because the Bishop on e7 plays a great role in defending the f6-Knight. On the other hand, this line is more ambitious because it keeps the Bishop pair on the board. It also gives Black the potential to outplay the opponent in the long run. The good news is that if you know how to handle this structure and understand the main plans and concepts, Black will have a hard time finding any active resources while White can build up the pressure slowly but steadily without much risk. }
7. Nge2
{ As a rule of thumb, you should not be afraid of ...Bg4 because we can play Qd3 and kick the Bishop later with h3, this way winning half a tempo. We could also start by playing  7.h3  because it's a useful move in this structure, but why not give Black the temptation of playing an active but inferior move? }
7... Be6 { Hitting the c4-pawn. } 8. b3
{ Now Black has a few ways to deviate from the most standard plan of playing ...Be7 and O-O. We will cover the small sidelines with independent value in the following lines andfocus on the most common lines on the 7... Be7 move order. }
8... Nd7
{ This is most likely going to transpose to normal lines, but Black also has an interesting plan of going for ...g6-g7. This plan is quite rare, but it's important to be aware of it because the play is a bit different. }
9. a4
{ This is the most precise move order! If Black plays  9...Be7  now, we are in time with  10.h3!  and we are ready to meet  10...O-O  with  11.g4!  getting back to the main line.   Now you can think that we could very well start with  9.h3  --  , and play  10.a4  ,  and if Black does the same, it is just going to be the same thing, but the problem with 9. h3 is that Black can go for ...g6 and it's no longer that smart to play our main idea with h4!? because we are losing an important tempo. Those are small nuances and might be difficult to understand at first, but in the long run, knowing these little things will help you dominate your opponents! }
9... Be7
{ Is most likely going totranspose to the 7... Be7 and 10... Nd7 line. } 10. h3
O-O 11. g4 { Transposing to the 7... Be7 and 10... Nd7 line. } *

