7... Be7 { I decided to make this the main move order as it's preparing O-O. }
8. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4 ideas, and preparing g4 in some positions. } 8... O-O
9. b3 { Not rushing with O-O because Black is fine after the ...Nd7-Bg5 plan. }
9... Be6
{ This is one of the main positions of the whole 4... Na5 line. Most people would just play  10.O-O  here and give Black the chance to get a comfortable game after  10...Nd7!  with the double threat of pushing ...f5 and playing ...Bg5. Here I find it best to stay flexible and play: }
10. a4
{ Played by former World Junior Champion Lu Shanglei, with the idea to meet ...Nd7 with g4! }
10... Nd7
{ Threatening to push ...f5 while also introducing ...Bg5 ideas. This plan works well when White castles short, but here you see why we postponed it: }
11. g4
{ Simply stopping Black's ...f5 break! Now you may be wondering where do we castle? The answer to that question is, we go Queenside! }
11... Bg5 { This remains Black's only idea, but White has an easy game after: }
12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3
{ Strangely enough, Lu Shanglei took with the pawn in his game, leading to a better position for Black! It was much simpler to take with the Queen and go for Queenside castling with an easy game for White. }
13... a5
{ Might seem logical with the idea to play ...Nc5 without allowing White to push b4, but this move is already bad! The problem with it is that Black has no pawn break now, and the b5-square has also been weakened. White has free play on the Kingside: }
14. O-O-O Nc5 15. Ng3 { Threatening Nf5. } 15... g6 16. f4
{ The simplest.   16.f3  With the idea to push h4 is logical, but Black has the annoying  16...Qh4∞  And the Queen is blocking our Kingside play. }
16... exf4 17. Qxf4 f6 18. Nge2
{ With an attacking position for White on the Kingside, who can continue with Nd4 and h4-h5. Meanwhile, Black lacks counterplay because of the early mistake with 13. a5?! }
