{ This is a bit more subtle, but Black is preparing to play ...g6 @@StartBracket@@which is mostly meant against our Ng3-Nf5 plan@@EndBracket@@ and then bring the Knight to g7 with ...f6/f5 ideas. The good news is that White can build up the pressure with natural moves: }
13. Ng3 { Threatening Nf5. } 13... g6 14. Bh6
{ Developing the Bishop with tempo. Forcing Black to play ...Ng7, as the exchange is otherwise lost. }
14... Ng7 15. Rd3
{ Preparing to double the Rooks on the d-file, putting pressure on the backward pawn on d6. Now Black has two main plans, he can either play passive or a bit more aggressive: }
15... f5 { Is the aggressive, but very risky plan. } 16. exf5 gxf5
{ Trying to keep the typical King's Indian pawns, but we can take advantage of the fact that the h5-square has been weakened: }
17. Nh5
{ Putting pressure on the Knight. Notice that ...e4 runs into Qg3! with mating threats. }
17... Bf6 18. Nxg7
{ We are simply going to get rid of the enemy dark-squared Bishop that could become active after ...e4 ideas, and then we have free pressure on the backward d6-pawn. }
18... Bxg7 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 { Forced, otherwise the pawn on d6 drops. } 20. Rad1
{ With really unpleasant pressure on the backward pawn. Notice that there is no need to be afraid of ...e4 ideas because White always has the Qg3+ intermezzo. }
