{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-d5. White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3, then pushing f4, after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   Not only is this set-up easy to play, but it is also quite effective. It puts a lot of pressure on both the center and the Kingside because White is considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4.   Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2... Nf6 because that would allow 3... Nxe4 ideas! This is important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Be7
{ Is a common move for online chess, but we see it much less frequently in OTB games compared to the big main lines because the Bishop is a little passive on e7. }
5. f4
{ We continue in the standard fashion, putting pressure in the center, preparing to play Nf3 next. }
5... d6 6. Nf3
{ So far, everything was pretty much forced, now Black has a choice between three different plans: }
6... Bg4
{ Going for the direct pin is common, especially in lower elos. The good news is that White ends up having the Bishop pair for free: }
7. h3 { Forcing the Bishop to choose his path. } 7... Bxf3
{ More or less forced because ...Bh5 was running into g4! trapping the Bishop. }
8. Qxf3 Na5 { Hunting the light-squared Bishop. } 9. Bb3
{ Forcing Black to open up the a-file if he wants to eliminate our Bishop. }
9... Nxb3 10. axb3 { Activating the Rook. } 10... c6 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne2
{ Preparing to bring the Knight to f5 via g3, with a pleasant position for White thanks to the more active Bishop and the open a-file. }
