5. f4
{ We are down to take the challenge! While this move looks risky at first, as there is no obvious way to castle short, White has a lot of pressure in both the center and on the Kingside, with the threat of pushing f5 followed by g4 always available. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3
{ The most natural and the best move in the position. This now opens a door for Black to play ...Ng4, but you need to know that White is generally fine after playing Qe2!   6.f5  Was tried by some people, but Black is getting good counterplay after  6...Nd4⇆  With ...c6 and ...d5 to come. Black has good play in the center. }
6... Ng4
{ Threatening to play ...Nf2, this is the only move that has some independent value as  6...d6  wouldtranspose back to the main lines. }
7. Qe2 { With the idea to meet ...Nf2 with the simple and strong Rf1! } 7...
exf4
{ Played by Vajda Levente. I doubt that a lot of people would refrain from touching the f2-square! }
8. Bxf4 d6 9. Bg5
{ This move is annoying for Black since there is no particular pleasant way to block the attack. }
9... Qd7 10. Rf1 { Keeping an eye on the f2-square. } 10... h6 11. Bf4 Nd4
{ A common idea for Black to prepare the ...c6-d5 counterplay. } 12. Nxd4 Bxd4
13. h3 Ne5 { Threatening ...Nxc4 } 14. Bb3
{ Keeping our Bishop on a nice and safe square. } 14... Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 a5
{ Threatening to push ...a4 } 16. a4
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the Bishop pair and attacking chances on the Kingside. To make the attack successful, you should think about using the h6-pawn as a hook because that will boost White's speed on the Kingside. }
