5. f4
{ We are down to take the challenge! While this move looks risky at first, as there is no obvious way to castle short, White has a lot of pressure in both the center and on the Kingside, with the threat of pushing f5 followed by g4 always available. }
5... h5
{ Played with the idea to meet  6.Nf3  with  ...Ng4  leading to some crazy complications. After analyzing those positions for a while, I concluded that Black should equalize with precise play. But then I realized that White has something even better: }
6. h3
{ Avoiding the crazy stuff arising after ...Ng4. Now White plans to continue his development by playing Nf3, and then Black's ...h5 move will become a weakness if Black sticks to ''normal'' play. }
6... d5
{ Black's only way to fight for a balanced game! This move was never played, and it is not an obvious pawn sacrifice at all, so I don't expect a lot of people to find this move! Nevertheless, White still keeps interesting play after: }
7. exd5 Nxd5 { Introducing ...Qh4 ideas. } 8. Nxd5 Be6
{ Going for the tempting  8...Qh4+  here would be a big mistake because White can answer with  9.Kd2!  and there is no good follow-up for Black. }
9. Qf3
{ This move is important for White because all the Knight retreats are bad because of ...Qh4 ideas, and therefore we must come up with a different way of protecting the d5-Knight. The drawback of Qf3 is that it gives Black an annoying jump with the Knight to d4, but the resulting positions are tricky: }
9... Nd4 10. Qe4
{ Keeping the strong Knight and allowing Black to go for the fork. The point is that the Knight will have a hard time coming back in the game after collecting the Rook! }
10... Nxc2+ 11. Kd2
{ This move might seem a bit counterintuitive because it's blocking the dark-squared Bishop, but the point is that the King protects the d3-pawn, which is very important in some lines! }
11... Nxa1 12. Nf3 c6
{ Black has to get rid of our strong Knight sooner or later. } 13. Nc3 Bxc4 14.
Qxc4 { Attacking the c5-Bishop. } 14... Be7 15. fxe5 O-O 16. b3
{ With a balanced position according to the engine, but I think that it's much easier to play with White since we are going to collect the trapped a1-Knight. If Black does not react adequately, White will be much better objectively speaking thanks to the small material advantage of having two minor pieces for the Rook. }
