5. f4
{ We are down to take the challenge! While this move looks risky at first, as there is no obvious way to castle short, White has a lot of pressure in both the center and on the Kingside, with the threat of pushing f5 followed by g4 always available. }
5... d6
{ Black's most popular answer, opening up the light-squared Bishop and stabilizing the situation in the center. }
6. Nf3
{ As we've seen previously, controlling the g5-square is useful for Black, but immediately doing it allows White to hunt the dark-squared Bishop with Na4! }
6... h6 7. Na4
{ The other typical plan with  7.f5  was not great here because Black's King is still in the center and it would have been premature to start pushing the Kingside pawns when Black has the option to castle Queenside. }
7... Bb6 { This is the typical reaction to Na4. } 8. Nxb6
{ Eliminating the dark-squared Bishop. } 8... axb6 9. O-O O-O 10. c3
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the good control over the center and the Bishop pair. White can continue with the prophylactic Bb3 followed by f5 and the standard Kingside play based on h3-g4. }
