{ White's plan is pretty straightforward:  -we trade off the f6-Knight  -we get a free hand on the Kingside with g4-g5 }
8... Nxd5 9. Bxd5 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 c6
{ Hitting the d5-Bishop and preparing to push ...d5! } 11. Bb3 d5
{ Black can try this pawn break because our f5-pawn will be hanging in most variations. Having that in mind, White's next move is very logical: }
12. Rf1 { Indirectly defending the f5-pawn and threatening exd5! } 12... a5
{ Threatening to trap the b3-Bishop with ...a4! } 13. a4
{ Avoiding Black's trick and reinforcing the exd5 threat! } 13... dxe4 14. Qxe4
{ I like taking with the Queen because if Black does nothing, we can simply play Bd2 followed by castling long with good control in the center and potential attacking chances on the Kingside. }
14... Qd4 { Black's safest option, getting rid of the Queens. } 15. c3
{ Forcing Black to enter the endgame in our terms! } 15... Qxe4+ 16. dxe4
{ With a pleasant endgame for White thanks to the more active light-squared Bishop and extra space on the Kingside. }
*

