{ This move is directed against Na4 ideas so that Black can save the Bishop by hiding it on a7. }
7. Nd5
{ Threatening the concrete fxe5 followed by Bg5 and also preparing to play to push the pawn to c3, controlling the important d4-square. Now Black has a bunch of options: }
7... Bg4 { Threatening ...Nd4! } 8. c3
{ One of the perks of having played Nd5 on the previous move, now White has good control over the d4-square! }
8... Ba7 9. h3 { Forcing Black to show his hand. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nxd5 11.
Bxd5
{ And White is dominating the board with the Bishop pair and can follow up with Bd2 and castle long with pressure on the Kingside. }
