{ This move is directed against Na4 ideas so that Black can save the Bishop by hiding it on a7. }
7. Nd5
{ Threatening the concrete fxe5 followed by Bg5 and also preparing to play to push the pawn to c3, controlling the important d4-square. Now Black has a bunch of options: }
7... Nxd5
{ The most common move in OTB chess, played by the legendary Spanish Grandmaster Vallejo Pons. }
8. Bxd5 exf4
{ The idea behind this move is to meet  9.Bxf4  with  ...Qf6!  ,  attacking the f4-Bishop and the b2-pawn. The good news is that White can be more ambitious with: }
9. d4
{ Creating a strong pawn center with tempo! Black can now either play passive and be slightly worse, or try to complicate the matters with a piece sacrifice: }
9... Bb6
{ Is the safer way of playing, but leads to a slightly passive position: } 10.
Bxf4 Be6 11. O-O O-O { Played by Paco Vallejo. } 12. Kh1
{ I love Wei's move! It immediately safeguards against any tactics from the b6-Bishop and c6-Knight. As we saw multiple times already in this course, it's always useful to play Kh1 once the f-pawn was pushed. }
12... h6
{ Black tried to defend against Bg5/Ng5 threats, but now the pawn becomes a target on h6! }
13. Qd2 { Threatening a mating attack with Bxh6! } 13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne7 15.
Bxh6
{ With a great initiative for White on the Kingside, despite missing the win later on in: ½-½ Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@-Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ Leon 2014 }
