[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Vienna Opening: 4... Bc5 & 5... d6"]
[Black "Vienna Opening: 4... Bc5 & 5... d6 with 6... Bg4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move, being the most played move against 1. e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles. Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot when compared to the romantic period of chess. The old masters abused the King's Gambit, attempting to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice.  Most of the current top players have switched to a more positional approach with 2. Nf3, seeking to play the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Although those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  , Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@, as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite Chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Nc6
{ The Max Lange Defense, named after the West German Champion from the nineteenth century, is mainly directed against the Vienna Gambit. If White goes for the brave  3.f4!?  Black can play  3...exf4  ,  creating an annoying threat of going ...Qh4+ next. If we compare this with the Falkbeer Variation, it's easy to notice that 3. f4 becomes viable because the presence of the f6-Knight blocks the Queen from reaching h4 as in the other line. }
3. Bc4
{ Transposing to a hybrid version of the Bishop's Opening! This works well here because we avoided Black's quick counterplay in the center based on ...c6-d5. White's idea is to follow up with the simple and strong plan of playing d3, then pushing f4, after which White can complete his development by playing Nf3 and O-O.   Not only is this set-up easy to play, but it is also quite effective. It puts a lot of pressure on both the center and the Kingside because White is considering ideas to push f5 and follow it up with a pawn storm with g4.   Before we move on to the more advanced stuff, I want you to remember that we can get this transposition to the Bishop's Opening only if Black is not playing 2... Nf6 because that would allow 3... Nxe4 ideas! This is important to understand right off the bat! }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ Very popular among OTB players, and by far the main move in online chess. Black is developing the Bishop on the most active square, trying to discourage White from playing f4 because the pressure along the a7-g1 diagonal will give White a hard time castling short. }
5. f4
{ We are down to take the challenge! While this move looks risky at first, as there is no obvious way to castle short, White has a lot of pressure in both the center and on the Kingside, with the threat of pushing f5 followed by g4 always available. }
5... d6
{ Black's most popular answer, opening up the light-squared Bishop and stabilizing the situation in the center. }
6. Nf3
{ The standard square for the g1-Knight once we have pushed f4 because we are putting a lot of pressure in the center this way. Please notice that White now has a subtle threat of going Na4, hunting the enemy dark-squared Bishop. }
6... Bg4
{ Black's most popular reply, creating an unpleasant threat of ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nd4!   6...exf4  This is Jan Gustafsson's move order, and it istransposing to the 5... exf4 lines. }
7. Na4
{ With the idea to eliminate the dark-squared Bishop and push the pawn to c3, controlling the d4-square. }
7... O-O 8. Nxc5 { The point of having played 7. Na4! } 8... dxc5 9. O-O Qd6
{ Connecting the Rooks and threatening ...exf4! } 10. Qd2
{ Defending the f4-pawn and threatening to trade everything on e5 and then play the strong Qg5! leading to a much better endgame for White. }
10... Bxf3 11. gxf3
{ Making the ...Nd4 plan less effective and potentially using the g-file in our favor!   11.Rxf3?!  Gives Black a lot of counterplay after  11...Nd4⇆  With ...b5 coming on the next move, Black has a comfortable position. }
11... exf4 12. Qxf4 { Offering a pretty one-sided set of endgames! } 12... Qxf4
{ Is leading to good endgames for White, but there is one little trick that you need to keep in mind: }
13. Bxf4 { Hitting the c7-pawn. } 13... b5
{ This is a tricky move, and it might scare a few people off, but you have to stay away from Bxb5 because Black has ...Nd4!, hitting the b5-Bishop and threatening the fork with ...Ne2+ }
14. Bb3
{ The good news is that we can stay away from the b5-pawn, and Black's issues are not gone! }
14... a5
{ Threatening to push ...a4! Here I suggest a small improvement over the Ginger GM game: }
15. a4
{ With a hanging Queenside!   15.c3∞  Was less convincing in the game: ½-½  (39)  Williams,S  (2511)  -Klauser,M  (2362)  Lenzerheide 2010 }
*

