{ The starting position for the Vienna Gambit, and already a critical moment for Black! What I love about this variation is that if Black doesn't play  3...d5  , he is much worse as early as move three! Besides that, we are in new territory and have unlimited room for analysis. }
3... d6
{ This move is, of course, inferior to thebig main line with  3...d5  , but at least it's better thanaccepting the bait with  3...exf4? }
4. Nf3
{ Putting pressure on the e5-pawn. Now Black has a couple of ways to deal with this threat: }
4... Nc6
{ The most natural way to defend against fxe5. Now White has an important move: }
5. Bb5 { Pinning the Knight and directly putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
5... Bd7 6. d3
{ Protecting the e4-pawn and threatening Bxc6 followed by fxe5 and the pawn drops. }
6... exf4 7. Bxf4 Be7 8. O-O O-O
{ And now there is nothing wrong with grabbing the center, but it might be even simpler to play: }
9. Qd2 a6 10. Bxc6
{ We don't mind giving up the Bishop here since it was already hard to keep it, and we sort of achieved what we wanted because Black had to give up the center and play ...exf4. }
10... Bxc6 11. Rae1
{ With Nd4-Nf5 being a very annoying threat, White has a small edge. } *

