{ The main move, making it tough for Black to develop the dark-squared Bishop while preparing a sneaky Be2-Bh5 maneuver! Black has two major moves, one recommended by Jan Gustafsson, and the other move championed by Sethuraman. }
8... dxc3 { Recommended by Jan in his Lifetime Repertoire. } 9. Be2
{ Creating a sneaky Bh5 threat because g6 can be met by the powerful Bxg6+! Bishop sacrifice when White has a winning attack! }
9... Be6
{ Jan's recommendation, with the idea to meet the Bishop sacrifice by playing ...Bf7! }
10. Bf3
{ Now that Bh5 was no longer effective due to ...g6, we can activate our Bishop by putting pressure on the b7-pawn at the same time. }
10... Nc6 { Threatening to jump around with ...Nd4/Nb4! } 11. Bxc6+
{ Eliminating Black's active counterplay. } 11... bxc6 12. Ne2
{ Preparing O-O and at some point to regain the c3-pawn. } 12... Qd7
{ Jan stops in his course here, saying that there is a complex fight ahead where Black should be fine after pushing ...h6 and g5. He is right in his assessment, but this is exactly what we are looking for! A complex fight where we can outplay our opponent because we have a better understanding of the position. I invite you to dive a little bit deeper into some of the possible continuations, although in my opinion, if you make it till here, you should be just fine. }
13. O-O
{ And now Black has a few plans to choose from besides Jan's aforementioned ...h6-g5 idea: }
13... h6
{ Preparing ...g5 is a very sound plan, but I feel like not everyone is that comfortable while pushing the Kingside pawns. }
14. Qf2 { Preparing Nxc3 without allowing the ...Qd4+ double attack! } 14... g5
15. Nxc3
{ With a complex position. It depends on how Black develops his dark-squared Bishop because if he goes after the e5-pawn by playing ...Bg7, then we get a nice initiative after Na4! with the idea to play Nc5 next. If he goes for ...Be7 instead, we can play Be3 followed by Bc5, trade the dark-squared Bishops, and then we have better control over the c5-square, and we can think of Na4-Nc5 ideas again. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Vienna Gambit"]
[Black "Vienna Gambit: 3... d5 & 5... f5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move, being the most played move against 1. e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles. Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot when compared to the romantic period of chess. The old masters abused the King's Gambit, attempting to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice.  Most of the current top players have switched to a more positional approach with 2. Nf3, seeking to play the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Although those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  , Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@, as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite Chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Nf6
{ The most common move in OTB chess by far, but a little bit less popular in online chess compared to  2...Nc6  . The big difference between these two seemingly similar-looking moves is that the  2...Nf6  variation gives Black an additional option to meet our ideal  3.Bc4  with  ...Nxe4  leading to some complications after the interesting  4.Qh5  move, where I believe Black should be fine.   The reason I skipped 3. Bc4, despite it being very playable, is that the arising positions might not suit everyone's taste, and I felt like a lot more people would be enjoying the Vienna Gambit. }
3. f4
{ The starting position for the Vienna Gambit, and already a critical moment for Black! What I love about this variation is that if Black doesn't play  3...d5  , he is much worse as early as move three! Besides that, we are in new territory and have unlimited room for analysis. }
3... d5 { Black's best reaction and the big main line. } 4. fxe5 Nxe4
{ The point of having played 3... d5! Black gets the e4-square for his Knight and solves the first problem. Black has some annoying ...Qh4+ ideas that we have to deal with now. The most natural way to block the check is to play the old main line with  5.Nf3  , but I am not a big fan of it because I feel like Black has plenty of ways to get a playable position. Therefore I recommend we try the more venomous and modern main line by playing: }
5. Qf3
{ Putting pressure on the e4-Knight and preparing to meet ...Qh4+ with g3! Of course, it looks a bit strange to develop the Queen this early in the game, but here we gain a tempo. Sometimes you have to do these things to get a new position with a lot of room to outplay your opponent @@StartBracket@@see the Harikrishna System from the Anti-Sicilian Toolkit@@EndBracket@@. }
5... f5
{ Recommended by both Gustafsson and Sethuraman in their Lifetime Repertoires! This is a very risky continuation, strategically speaking. The point is that it's connected with a very concrete approach, as White would otherwise get a much better position by default. }
6. d3 { Getting rid of the strong Knight. } 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ Now we are threatening to push d4 and get a much better position thanks to the solid situation in the center and a much more active light-squared Bishop. Therefore Black has to go for: }
7... d4
{ Very important, we would otherwise play d4 with a much better position as explained above. }
8. Qg3
{ The main move, making it tough for Black to develop the dark-squared Bishop while preparing a sneaky Be2-Bh5 maneuver! Black has two major moves, one recommended by Jan Gustafsson, and the other move championed by Sethuraman. }
8... Nc6 { Recommended by Sethuraman in his Lifetime Repertoire. } 9. Be2
{ Threatening the sneaky check on h5. } 9... Qd5
{ Could be an alternative with the idea to have ...Qf7 at the end of the line. It's also putting pressure on the e5-pawn. Nevertheless, I think I found an interesting try for White: }
10. c4 { Sacrificing the e5-pawn for positional compensation. } 10... Qxe5 11.
Bf4 { Developing the Bishop with tempo. } 11... Qf6 12. Bh5+
{ Forcing Black to play ...g6 and weaken the dark-squares around the Kingside. }
12... g6 13. Bf3 Bb4+
{ This check looks pretty annoying at first, but in reality, we can play: } 14.
Kd1
{ And White's King is very safe on d1. We can continue with Rb1 and Ne2, threatening all kinds of Bxc6+ followed by Be5, or we can push h4-h5, while it is not simple to even make a move as Black. I find it funny that even the weaker engines like Black here, giving a -/+ assessment while a strong computer is screaming the opposite, giving +/- ! }
*

