{ Back to the good old theory! From a historical point of view, this is Black's richest move, being the most played move against 1. e4 from beginner level to World Championship Cycles. Nowadays, the theory has developed a lot when compared to the romantic period of chess. The old masters abused the King's Gambit, attempting to refute Black's set-up with a very aggressive pawn sacrifice.  Most of the current top players have switched to a more positional approach with 2. Nf3, seeking to play the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@Spanish Opening@@EndBracket@@ or The Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@Italian Game@@EndBracket@@. Although those are the most principled openings, they also require an insane amount of theory and a good understanding of the upcoming middlegames to be played successfully.  Last but not least, I also want to make you aware that against  2.Nf3  , Black can also try to kill the game on the spot by playing the ultra-solid  2...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@Petroff Defense@@EndBracket@@, as most of the top Chinese Grandmasters, World number two Fabiano Caruana, and your favorite Chessable author Anish Giri do. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game! This Opening was always there, mostly played as a surprise weapon at the top level, but recently it got a nice boost thanks to Hikaru Nakamura and Alireza Firouzja. The main perks of the Vienna Game are that it avoids both the Berlin and Petroff Defense, which are two of Black's primary ways to kill the game before it begins!  I want you to pay attention to this precise move order because it is easy to mess things up if you don't truly understand what we are playing for. Now the simplest is to divide Black's options into two main alternatives, even though I've also covered the sidelines. Black's two main options are:   2...Nf6  known as The Falkbeer Variation   2...Nc6  The Max Lange Defense }
2... Nf6
{ The most common move in OTB chess by far, but a little bit less popular in online chess compared to  2...Nc6  . The big difference between these two seemingly similar-looking moves is that the  2...Nf6  variation gives Black an additional option to meet our ideal  3.Bc4  with  ...Nxe4  leading to some complications after the interesting  4.Qh5  move, where I believe Black should be fine.   The reason I skipped 3. Bc4, despite it being very playable, is that the arising positions might not suit everyone's taste, and I felt like a lot more people would be enjoying the Vienna Gambit. }
3. f4
{ The starting position for the Vienna Gambit, and already a critical moment for Black! What I love about this variation is that if Black doesn't play  3...d5  , he is much worse as early as move three! Besides that, we are in new territory and have unlimited room for analysis. }
3... d5 { Black's best reaction and the big main line. } 4. fxe5 Nxe4
{ The point of having played 3... d5! Black gets the e4-square for his Knight and solves the first problem. Black has some annoying ...Qh4+ ideas that we have to deal with now. The most natural way to block the check is to play the old main line with  5.Nf3  , but I am not a big fan of it because I feel like Black has plenty of ways to get a playable position. Therefore I recommend we try the more venomous and modern main line by playing: }
5. Qf3
{ Putting pressure on the e4-Knight and preparing to meet ...Qh4+ with g3! Of course, it looks a bit strange to develop the Queen this early in the game, but here we gain a tempo. Sometimes you have to do these things to get a new position with a lot of room to outplay your opponent @@StartBracket@@see the Harikrishna System from the Anti-Sicilian Toolkit@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nc6
{ This is an interesting idea meant to answer the most natural  6.Nxe4  with the strong  ...Nd4!  and Black has very good counterplay. The good news is that we can pin the c6-Knight and avoid the crazy lines by playing: }
6. Bb5
{ Pinning the potentially dangerous Knight and renewing the Nxe4 threat. Most of the time, Black decides to force an endgame by playing  6...Nxc3  followed by  7.--  Qh4+  with ...Qe4+ to come. On the other hand, I've noticed a considerable amount of ways to deviate for Black that have been tried in online chess, and I decided that it's worth adding them: }
6... Nxc3 { The main line of 5... Nc6!? } 7. dxc3 { Opening up the c1-Bishop. }
7... Bc5 { Allows White to hit the g7-pawn: } 8. Qg3
{ And suddenly Black is in trouble because there is no easy way to deal with the threat over the g7-pawn. }
8... O-O { Does not fix the issue for Black because of: } 9. Bh6
{ Forces Black to give up the exchange to prevent getting mated. } *

