{ Very committal and strong! When I first came across this idea, strategically speaking, it looked a bit risky because we are giving Black the d5-square. The point is that White is too fast with Bc4, Nc3, and Qb3 ideas, and Black can't make good use of the d5-square. }
6... Nd5 7. Qb3
{ All of a sudden, Black has problems with the b7-pawn because ...Qc8 drops the d5-Knight. }
7... Bc8 { Solving the issue with the b7-pawn, but it's just too passive: } 8.
Bg5 { Making it tricky for Black to develop the dark-squared Bishop. } 8... h6
9. Bc4
{ Giving away the g5-Bishop for the d5-Knight because White will end up having a double-attack on the b7- and f7-pawns. }
9... c6 10. Bh4 g5
{ Weakening the Kingside to develop the dark-squared Bishop. } 11. Bg3 Bg7 12.
Nc3 { Increasing the pressure over the d5-Knight. } 12... O-O 13. O-O
{ We don't rush with taking on d5 since Black would have gotten some unwanted counterplay with ...Nc6. Now White can continue with Rfe1 and also remind Black about the weakened Kingside with h4! }
