ning again to draw with Caruana at the 2016 Chess Olympiad at Baku.  @@HeaderStart@@Nowadays experts@@HeaderEnd@@ The biggest experts for the Black side of the Scandinavian that are implementing it regularly in their tournament practice in our time are:  - Grandmaster Sergey Tiviakov from the Netherlands @@StartBracket@@not only did he play the opening a lot, but he also wrote many articles about it, developing the theory@@EndBracket@@.  - Grandmaster Igor Kovalenko from Latvia. }
2. exd5 Qxd5
{ The Mieses-Kotroc Variation. This is the most popular move among the Black players when going for the Scandinavian Defense. Everyone plays the automatic  3.Nc3  move in this position, attacking the early developed Queen and then stepping into the center with d4. Despite the objective value of 3. Nc3, it requires a lot of knowledge in a variety of lines because Black has three viable options:   •  3...Qa5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  3...Qd6  @@StartBracket@@The Gubinsky-Melts Defense, developed by Sergey Tiviakov@@EndBracket@@  •  3...Qd8  @@StartBracket@@with the idea to play ...Nf6-g6-Bg7@@EndBracket@@ is also fashionable nowadays.   Another playable variation for White is the  3. Nf3-line, which is a pretty standard way to avoid the crazy theoretical lines while keeping a small positional edge. This variation is quite similar to my recommendation, but the main drawback of the line is that Black can force a balanced endgame after the precise  3...Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  . Now it's nice for White to include  5.h3  , and Black's best option is to go for  ...Bxf3!  6.Bxf3  . The big point is to play  ...Qe6+!  now, when White has nothing better than to trade Queens with  7.Qe2  . Black is very active in exchange for the Bishop pair. Now that you have a decent overview of White's choices, I think we can move on to my recommendation: }
3. d4
{ The point of this move is to play c4 followed by Nc3, avoiding one of the main issues that White has in the  3.Nc3  main lines. ➼ The d4-pawn can become vulnerable if White does not play the opening properly. Most of the time, we will transpose into the  3.Nf3  lines in a way where we avoid the aforementioned endgame! Of course, Black has some ways to deviate from the transposition, but we are going to analyze all of them in great depth. }
3... Qa5+
{ The Queen making another unprovoked move is not logical, but some people might desperately try to get in their ...Qa5 lines, so I think it's worth knowing at least how to arrange your pieces. }
4. c3
{ Keep in mind that we don't want to play  4.Nc3  andtranspose to the main lines. It's much better to play the small pawn move, and then we can potentially hunt the enemy Queen with Nd2-Nc4 ideas. }
4... Nf6 5. Nd2 { Creating an unpleasant Nc4 threat. } 5... c6
{ Creating a square for the Queen on c7. } 6. Ngf3 Qc7 7. Bd3
{ Preparing O-O. } 7... g6
{ Black is trying to restrict the potential of our light-squared Bishop by setting up the fianchetto. You need to keep in mind that our c3-d4 structure will restrict the g7-Bishop, so we end up fine from this 'positional duel'. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1
{ With an easy game for White who can continue with move such as Nc4, Qe2 ➼ putting pressure on the e-file, and then I like the Bg5-Bh4-Bg3 maneuver, giving the enemy Queen a hard time in finding a safe place. }
