3. d4
{ The point of this move is to play c4 followed by Nc3, avoiding one of the main issues that White has in the  3.Nc3  main lines. ➼ The d4-pawn can become vulnerable if White does not play the opening properly. Most of the time, we will transpose into the  3.Nf3  lines in a way where we avoid the aforementioned endgame! Of course, Black has some ways to deviate from the transposition, but we are going to analyze all of them in great depth. }
3... Qe6+
{ This questionable line could be played by someone who just watched the viral chess24 videos on YouTube with Magnus Carlsen trolling people during his banter blitz sessions. Despite not being the most valuable line from a theoretical point of view, I think the refutation is still instructive: }
4. Be2 Qg6
{ Hitting the g2-pawn. Now it's best to ignore Black's threat and focus on development! }
5. Nf3 { Sacrificing the g2-pawn for a lead in development. } 5... Qxg2 6. Rg1
{ Activating the Rook. } 6... Qh3 7. Rg3
{ Forcing the Queen to an awkward square. } 7... Qd7 8. Nc3
{ With a big edge for White, who can continue by playing Bf4 and Qd2 followed by castling long. While assessing these positions, it is important to know that a pawn is usually worth two tempi in the opening. As you can see here, White has three pieces developed and an active Rook for the sacrificed pawn, which is obviously, more than enough. }
