{ Avoiding the ...e5 ideas and preparing to continue with normal moves. Now Black has to decide what to do with the light-squared Bishop. He can either play:  •  5...Bg4   •  5...Bf5   •  5...e6  @@StartBracket@@playing with the passive Bishop@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6  @@StartBracket@@postponing the decision@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Planning to fianchetto the light-squared Bishop by playing ...b6 and ...Bb7, but this allows White to develop the Bishop to d3! }
6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bd3
{ Because there is no pressure on the f3-Knight now, we can develop the Bishop on the most active square! }
7... O-O 8. O-O b6 { Preparing to play ...Bb7 } 9. Bf4
{ The most active square for the Bishop. } 9... Bb7 10. Qe2
{ Preparing to play Rad1. } 10... Nc6 11. Rad1
{ With a comfortable edge for White, who can continue with Bb1 followed by Ne5. Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2832@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2786@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2018 }
