3. d4
{ The point of this move is to play c4 followed by Nc3, avoiding one of the main issues that White has in the  3.Nc3  main lines. ➼ The d4-pawn can become vulnerable if White does not play the opening properly. Most of the time, we will transpose into the  3.Nf3  lines in a way where we avoid the aforementioned endgame! Of course, Black has some ways to deviate from the transposition, but we are going to analyze all of them in great depth. }
3... Nc6 { Black's main move, putting immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. } 4.
Nf3
{ Defending the d4 pawn, and threatening to get the standard bind with c4 and Nc3. }
4... Bg4
{ Black's main move, putting pressure in the center and preparing O-O-O. } 5.
c4
{ Could be an interesting alternative besides  5.Nc3  if you are looking for a complex game. Black is most likely going to transpose to another big tabia of the 3. Nf3 Scandi after  5...Qh5 }
5... Qh5 6. Be2 O-O-O 7. Be3
{ And Black has a choice between:  •  7...Nf6   •  7...e5   •  7...Nh6    Those could be worth analyzing if you get tired of the 5. Nc3 line. }
