3... Nc6 { Black's main move, putting immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. } 4.
Nf3
{ Defending the d4 pawn, and threatening to get the standard bind with c4 and Nc3. }
4... Bg4
{ Black's main move, putting pressure in the center and preparing O-O-O. } 5.
Nc3 { Setting up a trap because White gets a big edge after  5...Bxf3? } 5...
Qa5
{ The Queen is less active on this squarecompared to the main  5...Qh5  move. }
6. Bb5 { The key move against these ...Nc6 lines. } 6... O-O-O 7. Bxc6
{ The point of having played Bb5! Black's Queenside is pretty vulnerable. }
7... bxc6 { Threatening to push ...e5! } 8. Qe2
{ Avoiding the ...e5 push, and offering a small bait on d4! } 8... Nf6
{ The safer alternative. } 9. O-O e6 10. h3
{ This small move is very important because we want to get rid of the annoying pin along the d1-h5 diagonal. }
10... Bh5 11. g4
{ The key move to get rid of the pin and use the f3-Knight to its full potential. Black could try to sacrifice the piece on g4, but it is not particularly threatening, as you will see in the Nigel Short game. }
11... Nxg4
{ This is always something that you need to consider when making such a committal move as g4, but White has it all under control after: }
12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. Qe4
{ The point! Now Ne5 becomes a huge threat, so Black has to get rid of our Knight. }
13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Rxd4
{ Black gets three pawns for the piece, but White is safe after: } 15. Be3
{ We can continue with Rfd1 on the next move, and the piece is much more useful than the pawns in this situation because the enemy King is vulnerable. White went on to win in: Short,N @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@-Zakarian,D @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@ England 2015 }
*

