9... dxe5 10. fxe5 c5 { Black's only source of counterplay. } 11. d5 Bc8 12.
Rc1
{ Allowing Black to play ...Bxe5 because we can meet it with Nf3 followed by Bxc5. }
12... N6d7 { Threatening ...Bxe5. } 13. Nf3 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxc5
{ Eliminating the important c5-pawn. White now has a four against two majority on the Queenside that could be very dangerous in a later phase of the game. }
15... Qc7 { Hitting the c5-Bishop and the h2-pawn. } 16. Bd4
{ It's simply not a big deal if Black takes on h2 because that will open up the h-file for our Rook! }
16... Bxh2 17. Qd2 { Threatening Qh6. } 17... Bf4 18. Be3
{ We are happy to trade off the dark-squared Bishops because Black's King will be vulnerable. }
18... Bg3+ 19. Kf1
{ The King is quite safe on this square, and the h1-Rook is very active, so the fact that we have not castled is not relevant. }
19... Nd7 20. Ne4
{ Threatening Nxg3, and if Black goes ...Be5, then c5 becomes an interesting idea, making use of the Queenside majority. White went on to win in: Akram,F @@StartBracket@@2230@@EndBracket@@-Wittal,W @@StartBracket@@2094@@EndBracket@@ IECC email 2018 }
