{ The most ambitious approach, and generally what your opponent hates to see! The point is that we can answer  5...dxe5  with  6.fxe5!  , avoiding the potential Queen trade on the d-file, and White manages to keep a strong center.   Now Black can choose between a variety of moves:  •  5...dxe5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... dxe5 { This is by far the most played move in both OTB and online chess. }
6. fxe5 c5
{ This super provocative move was played quite often back in the days, but it doesn't seem to have too many followers in the recent period. My guess is that this line is too risky for a practical game, despite the fact that Black managed to hold in some correspondence games. }
7. d5
{ Building a massive pawn center. Now Black can choose between:  •  7...g6   •  7...e6 }
7... e6 { Introducing ...Qh4+ ideas, but White's center is simply too strong: }
8. Nc3 exd5 9. cxd5 Qh4+ { With the idea to play ...Qd4 next. } 10. g3 Qd4 11.
Bb5+
{ It's best to avoid the Queen trade here, because if we try to play the same way as against 8... Qh4+ Black will have ...Nxd5! after Nb5. }
11... Bd7 12. Qe2
{ We are going to play Nf3 next, hitting the Black Queen with a much better position. Keep in mind that ...Nxd5 is going to be met by the crushing e6-move! }
