1. e4 Nf6
{ The Alekhine Defense. Black tempts the White pawns to move forward and form a board pawn center, with plans to undermine and attack the White structure later.  @@HeaderStart@@History@@HeaderEnd@@ The opening is named after Alexander Alekhine, who introduced it in the 1921 Budapest tournament in games against Endre Steiner and Fritz Sämisch.  @@HeaderStart@@Top Level Reputation@@HeaderEnd@@ The Alekhine's Defense was more popular in the past. For instance, Fischer used it in two games against Boris Spassky in the World Chess Championship 1972, and Korchnoi also included the defense in his repertoire, leading to its respectable reputation.   Nowadays, the Alekhine's defense is not so common at the top level. De Firmian observes, 'The fashion could quickly change if some champion of the opening takes up the cause, as the results Black has obtained in practice are good.' While the opening's current highest-rated proponent is GM Vassily Ivanchuk, Lev Alburt played it at grandmaster-level almost exclusively during his career and was responsible for many contributions in both theory and practice.   Currently, grandmasters Shabalov and Minasian regularly use the opening, while Aronian, Adams, and Nakamura occasionally use it. Carlsen does not employ the opening frequently, but he has used it occasionally in competitive games. Most notably, he defeated the former World Chess Champion Topalov in Linares 2008, employing the Alekhine's defense. }
2. e5
{ The most ambitious approach, accepting the challenge, we are going to build a massive pawn center. Before we dive into the main line theory, I want to quickly mention that as Vienna players, we have the option of playing  2.Nc3  , which couldtranspose to the Vienna if Black plays  2...e5  . But there are some lines you need to study if Black wants to deviate by going  2...d5  . }
2... Nd5 3. c4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ Attacking the d5-Knight, forcing it to b6. Another alternative is to play  2.d4  d6  . The big main line is now to go  3.Nf3  with a lot of theory and small nuances that you need to understand to get anything. I played that a couple of times, but it feels to me that it requires a bit too much effort for such a rare opening where the Black players generally know it well, and it could get pretty annoying to dive into their preparation. }
3... Nb6 4. d4
{ Setting up a strong pawn center. If you are looking for a fancy line,  4.a4  a5  5.Ra3  ➼ heading towards the g3-square could give you a fun game, but it's also double-edged. }
4... d6
{ The only move to not get a losing position on the spot! Black is threatening to play ...dxe5, heading towards a much better endgame because our e5-pawn will be a bit overextended. Of course, we are not allowing such things, and we will play  5.f4!  going for the most principled and aggressive continuation.  •  5.exd6  is another playable line for White, but leading to more balanced positions. }
5. f4
{ The most ambitious approach, and generally what your opponent hates to see! The point is that we can answer  5...dxe5  with  6.fxe5!  , avoiding the potential Queen trade on the d-file, and White manages to keep a strong center.   Now Black can choose between a variety of moves:  •  5...dxe5  @@StartBracket@@The main line@@EndBracket@@  •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... dxe5 { This is by far the most played move in both OTB and online chess. }
6. fxe5 Nc6 { Developing the Knight and putting pressure on the d4-pawn. } 7.
Be3
{ This move is important because it's the only way to defend the d4-pawn properly.  7.Nf3  would have allowed the oldest trick in the book with  ...Bg4  ,  and Black gets the dream scenario where he has good play against our pawns. Keep in mind that once we see Black commit with ...Bf5, then it's a good time to play Nf3 because he would have to waste a precious tempo to pin our Knight. }
7... Bf5
{ The main move for Black, with the idea to play ...e6 next without locking the light-squared Bishop. }
8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 { The main tabia of the line. Black has a big choice: } 9...
Nb4
{ Threatening the fork with ...Nc2+ and preparing to break in the center with ...c5 }
10. Rc1
{ Defending against the fork and preparing to kick the b4-Knight by pushing a3. }
10... c5 11. a3 { Forcing Black to take on d4, otherwise ...Nc6 runs into d5! }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4
{ Now Black is dealing with two unpleasant threats:  • the Knight on b4 is hanging  • Nxf5 is looming }
12... Nc6 13. Nxf5 { Taking the Bishop pair and doubling Black's pawns. } 13...
Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 exf5 15. Nb5
{ And White is much better because  15...Rc8  runs into  Nxa7! } *

