{ And now Black has a variety of plans. Most people tend to break in the center with  11...f6  ,  whichtransposes to the 5... Bf5 and 8... Be7 move order. }
11... Qd7 { Preparing to play Rad8. } 12. Qd2 { Preparing Rad1. } 12... Rad8
13. Rad1 f6
{ Has to be played. Black is otherwise getting suffocated by White's space advantage. }
14. exf6 Bxf6 15. b3 { A small useful move, defending the c4-pawn. } 15... Qe7
16. Qc1
{ Simply avoiding any tactical motifs that could appear on the d-file. White can improve his position by playing h3 @@StartBracket@@avoiding ...Bg4-ideas@@EndBracket@@ and then Bf2 followed by Qe3 seems to be very useful because White has good control in the center. }
*

