1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch Defense. Named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who was a Latvian-born Danish chess player and writer. He was the foremost figure amongst the hypermodern and wrote a very influential book on chess theory ''My System''. In the late 1920s, he was one of the best chess players in the world. }
2. d4 d6 { The Mikenas Variation. } 3. d5
{ Going for an improved version of the King's Indian! } 3... Nb8
{ The safer alternative. } 4. c4
{ Don't worry if you never played 1. d4 before! White is getting a nice and simple plan in this improved version of the King's Indian. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { Defending the e4-pawn. } 5... g6 6. Bd3
{ The easiest set-up! We are going to play Nge2 followed by O-O, with simple play. }
6... Bg7 7. Nge2 { This seems to be the best set-up for White. } 7... O-O 8.
O-O
{ And Black has a few plans to choose from, but none of them seem particularly threatening. }
8... e6 9. h3 { Preparing to play Be3 without allowing ...Ng4! } 9... exd5 10.
cxd5 Re8 11. Ng3 { Keeping the e4-pawn well defended. } 11... Nbd7 12. Be3 Nc5
{ Threatening to eliminate the light-squared Bishop. } 13. Bc2
{ With easy play for White. The plan is to go Qd2, Rae1, and then push f4 followed by Bd4, and the attack is playing itself. }
