[White "10. Owen's Defense"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1... b6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Owen Defense. The opening is named after the English vicar and strong 19th-century amateur chess player John Owen, an early exponent. Using his opening, Owen defeated Paul Morphy in an informal game in London, 1858. }
2. d4 Bb7
{ Developing the Bishop and attacking the e4-pawn. In a way similar to the St. George Defense, but without having the overextended Queenside which White used to attack. }
3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 c5
{ This is the main move in OTB chess and a logical one. The point is that Black wants to play ...cxd4 and get back to a position that is similar to the Paulsen Sicilian. We don't want to transpose to something that we don't know how to play, so we are going to stick with the stronger alternative, which is a surprising pawn sacrifice: }
6. d5
{ Giving up a pawn in a slightly surprising fashion, but White gets a strong initiative right off the bat. }
6... exd5 7. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black has to accept the sacrifice. He otherwise has no counterplay. } 8. Nxd5
Bxd5 9. O-O
{ This gentle move is causing the most problems for Black! We are ready to play Nf4 on the next move. }
9... Be7
{ I found out that a lot of people prefer this move in online chess, with the idea to castle short next. This is natural, but there is a very nice way for us to exploit it: }
10. Nf4 { Attacking the d5-Bishop. } 10... Bb7 11. Re1
{ Activating the Rook and baiting Black to castle short! } 11... O-O 12. Qh5
{ Setting up a double sacrifice on g6. Black is just lost! } 12... g6 13. Nxg6
{ The first one. It is important to take with the Knight first because after Bxg6 Black will be forced to recapture the Knight due to the checkmate on h7. }
13... fxg6 14. Bxg6 { Threatening to mate with Qh7. } 14... hxg6 15. Qxg6+
{ Forcing Black's King in the corner. } 15... Kh8 16. Re5
{ With Rh5 next, Black is getting mated. } *

