[White "10. Owen's Defense"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1... b6 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Owen Defense. The opening is named after the English vicar and strong 19th-century amateur chess player John Owen, an early exponent. Using his opening, Owen defeated Paul Morphy in an informal game in London, 1858. }
2. d4 Bb7
{ Developing the Bishop and attacking the e4-pawn. In a way similar to the St. George Defense, but without having the overextended Queenside which White used to attack. }
3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 d5 6. e5 Nfd7
{ This move is begging for a direct attack after: } 7. Nf4
{ Threatening a deadly attack after Nxe6 and Qh5+ } 7... g6
{ Stopping the direct Nxe6. } 8. Qg4 { Threatening Nxe6 followed by Bxg6! }
8... Qe7 { Defending against Nxe6, but weakening the c7-square. } 9. Nb5
{ Creating a threat of Nxc7. } 9... Na6 10. h4
{ Threatening to push h5, and weaken the enemy Kingside. } 10... h5 11. Qg3
{ With Nxg6 being in the air, Black is struggling to get a good night's sleep. }
