1. e4 b6
{ The Owen Defense. The opening is named after the English vicar and strong 19th-century amateur chess player John Owen, an early exponent. Using his opening, Owen defeated Paul Morphy in an informal game in London, 1858. }
2. d4 Bb7
{ Developing the Bishop and attacking the e4-pawn. In a way similar to the St. George Defense, but without having the overextended Queenside which White used to attack. }
3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 d5 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nb1
{ Threatening to trap the enemy Knight all of a sudden! } 7... c5
{ With the idea to meet f3 by ...c4! } 8. c3
{ Keeping a healthy pawn center and reinforcing the f3-idea. } 8... cxd4 9.
cxd4 Bb4+
{ Forcing us to block the check with a piece, meaning that the e4-Knight is safe for now. }
10. Nbc3 O-O 11. O-O f5 { Strengthening the Knight on e4. } 12. Nf4
