[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Owen's Defense"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1... b6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ The Owen Defense. The opening is named after the English vicar and strong 19th-century amateur chess player John Owen, an early exponent. Using his opening, Owen defeated Paul Morphy in an informal game in London, 1858. }
2. d4 Bb7
{ Developing the Bishop and attacking the e4-pawn. In a way similar to the St. George Defense, but without having the overextended Queenside which White used to attack. }
3. Nc3 e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nge2 d5 6. e5 Ng8 7. Nb1
{ Subtle and strong! If Black can take a moment and play ...Ng8 with the idea to undermine our center with ...c5, why wouldn't we invest a tempo to be able to keep it with c3?   7.Nf4⇆  This move would have been ideal, butcompared to the 6... Nfd7 line, the sacrifice on e6 is no longer effective because Black's King can escape by using the d7-square to run away!  7...c5  And Black is getting unnecessary counterplay. The Knight sac is not working:  8.Nxe6?  This wasthe point against the 6... Nfd7 variation, but it no longer works:  8...fxe6  9.Qh5+  And now Black can get away by playing:  9...Kd7-+  And Black remains up a piece. Notice that this move was not possible in the 6... Nfd7 line! }
7... Ba6
{ This is a typical idea to trade off the bad Bishop, but it's a bit slow, and White is still better thanks to the extra space. }
8. Bxa6 { Misplacing the Knight first. } 8... Nxa6 9. c3
{ Protecting the center and preparing to maneuver the b1-Knight all the way to f3. }
9... Qd7 10. Nd2 { Heading towards f3. } 10... c5 11. Nf3
{ Keeping the d4-square well protected. } 11... Nb8
{ Black has to bring the Knight back in the game via c6. } 12. O-O Nc6 13. Ng3
{ Heading towards h5! The Knight will be annoying for Black, who is going to have a hard time castling short. }
13... Nge7 14. Nh5
{ We can continue with Bd2-Rb1 followed by b4 while Black is struggling to find a safe place for his King. }
*

[Event "?"]
