[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defense! This opening is giving White a free edge because it's not influencing the center in any way. It became famous after Tony Miles used it to beat the reigning World Champion Anatoly Karpov at the European Team Championship in Skara in 1980. }
2. d4 b5 { Preparing to play ...Bb7 ➼ attacking the e4-pawn. } 3. Nf3
{ Developing the Knight on the natural square. Keep in mind that this move can be made automatically, while we are less happy about going Nc3 because of a potential ...b4-move that could be annoying. }
3... Bb7 { Hitting the e4-pawn. } 4. Bd3
{ Simply defending the pawn and preparing a short castle. Now Black can choose from two different plans:  •  4...e6  @@StartBracket@@the cautious move@@EndBracket@@  •  4...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@the aggressive approach@@EndBracket@@ }
4... Nf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn but inviting White to push in the center. This ambitious move was Tony's choice in his famous win against Karpov, but I suggest a small improvement over their game, even though White still got a decent edge. }
5. e5
{ We should accept the challenge and punish Black for his choice! The positional approach with  5.Qe2  is also fine, but it's showing a bit too much respect to this opening and backfired later in the famous Karpov,A @@StartBracket@@2725@@EndBracket@@-Miles,A @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@ Skara 1980. }
5... Nd5 6. O-O e6 7. a4
{ This small positional move is so venomous that Black has to either overextend with ...b4 or to accept the isolated pawn after ...bxa4. None of those moves are particularly pleasant to make, but this is the price that Black has to pay for choosing this opening. }
7... b4 { The most natural move. } 8. c4
{ Attacking the d5-Knight, and more or less forcing Black to go for the en passant. }
8... bxc3 9. bxc3 Be7 10. Be4
{ Threatening to win material with c4 next, Black has to make an ugly ...Ra7 move to stay in the game @@StartBracket@@which could be answered by c4 and d5@@EndBracket@@. }
