[Black "The St. George Defense: 1... a6 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 a6
{ The St. George Defense! This opening is giving White a free edge because it's not influencing the center in any way. It became famous after Tony Miles used it to beat the reigning World Champion Anatoly Karpov at the European Team Championship in Skara in 1980. }
2. d4 b5 { Preparing to play ...Bb7 ➼ attacking the e4-pawn. } 3. Nf3
{ Developing the Knight on the natural square. Keep in mind that this move can be made automatically, while we are less happy about going Nc3 because of a potential ...b4-move that could be annoying. }
3... Bb7 { Hitting the e4-pawn. } 4. Bd3
{ Simply defending the pawn and preparing a short castle. Now Black can choose from two different plans:  •  4...e6  @@StartBracket@@the cautious move@@EndBracket@@  •  4...Nf6  @@StartBracket@@the aggressive approach@@EndBracket@@ }
4... e6 { Preparing to push ...c5, this is Black's best plan. } 5. O-O c5
{ Threatening to play ...cxd4 and get a Paulsen type of Sicilian, or even ...c4 in some positions with the idea that the e4-pawn could become vulnerable. }
6. c3
{ Of course, we will not allow Black to get rid of our nice pawn center easily. We are ready to recapture with the pawn on d4 and keep our nice space advantage. }
6... Nf6 { Threatening ...Nxe4! } 7. Re1
{ Defending the e4-pawn and activating the Rook. } 7... Be7 8. e5
{ Gaining space and driving the night away from the Kingside. } 8... Nd5 9.
dxc5
{ The point! We are forcing Black to waste another move with the dark-squared Bishop while we plan to play Nbd2-Ne4, gaining another tempo! }
9... Bxc5 10. Nbd2
{ Preparing to play Ne4 on the next move. Keep in mind that ...Qb6 is not bothering us since the Knight will also defend the f2-pawn from e4! }
10... Nc6 11. Ne4
{ Centralizing the Knight while attacking the c5-Bishop and hinting to the d6-square. }
11... Be7 12. Bg5
{ Trading Black's dark-squared Bishop so that we can use the d6-square. White is dominating the position once the Knight arrives on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kryakvin, Dmitry vs. Gutov, Andrey"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ Kryakvin starts with the Bishop's Opening, but we are going to transpose to our beloved Vienna shortly, so you can just skip this part and jump to the 4th move. Just keep in mind that we start with  2.Nc3! }
2... Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3
{ Notice that we magically transposed to the main tabia of the Vienna! Now Black has a variety of playable moves. I will just name the main lines:  •  4...Bc5   •  4...Bb4   •  4...Na5 }
4... Bb4
{ This line is usually connected with the ...d5 break, as otherwise, the Bishop does not make a lot of sense on b4. }
5. Ne2 d5
{ The point of the previous move. Black strikes in the center hoping for a direct way to equalize. }
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O
{ Now Black has to do something with the d5-Knight. The most common way of playing is to defend it as in the game with  7...Be6  , but over time people have tried the other moves as well, such as  7...Nxc3  or  7...Nb6  . For more details make sure to check out the theory chapter of this course. }
7... Be6
{ Defending the d5-Knight and threatening to take on c3 with the Knight. } 8.
Bxd5
{ Yes, we are giving up the Bishop for absolutely no reason! This may look very strange at first, but it's a really modern concept. White is going to push f4 next with annoying play on the Kingside. }
8... Bxd5 9. f4
{ The point of 8. Bxd5! For example, it's now easy to lose the thread and play a normal-looking move like  9...exf4  and White is suddenly winning right off the bat after  10.Nxf4! }
9... O-O
{ The most played move by far, in both OTB and online chess. I expect you to face this a lot, and keep in mind the following trick because most of the White players are not using the best version! Before we move on, I want to give an honorable mention to  9...f6!?  , which is Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire and it gave me a lot of headaches while working on this repertoire. For more details about that, make sure to check out the theory chapter. }
10. f5
{ Dimitry plays in the most common fashion, but in my opinion, this is not the best version because it allows Black to get rid of the dark-squared Bishop by playing  10...Bxc3!   10.Nxd5!  Keeping Black's dark-squared Bishop on the board because it might end up out of the game since we are going to dominate on the light-squares.  10...Qxd5  11.f5↑  Check out the theory chapter for a detailed analysis of this position. }
10... f6 11. Ng3 { Preparing to get the Knight to e4. } 11... Ne7
{ Black is doing a big positional misunderstanding here because it allows White to get the Knight to e4 under good conditions. Something similar was happening in case of the most popular  11...Bf7  .  If you are passionate about the numbers, keep in mind that against 11... Bf7 White has a 70% win rate, while against the best move  11...Bxc3  , White's win rate is dropping to 44% only. It might seem a bit confusing why this is the case now, but let's just stick with the game so you understand! }
12. Nce4
{ The Bishop remains out of play on the Queenside while White is getting the initiative on the Kingside. }
12... Nc8 { Black might be trying to get his Knight to d6 in some positions. }
13. Qg4
{ Already threatening Nh5 because ...Rf7 fails to Nexf6+! winning on the spot. }
13... Kh8 14. Be3
{ Threatening  14...--  15.Nxf6  --  and  16.Qxb4!  Notice that taking on f6 instead of 14. Be3 was not a good idea because Black had 14... Bc5+! with a winning position. }
14... Be7 15. Nh5 Rf7 16. Rf3
{ The typical Rook lift! The Rook is heading towards the h-file. } 16... Bxe4
17. Qxe4
{ Keeping the tempo up, hitting the b7-pawn!   17.dxe4?!  Gives Black time to play:  17...Qf8∞  With ...Bc5 on the next move, looks like Black's position is defendable. }
17... c6 18. Rh3 { The Rook is eyeing the h7-square. } 18... Bf8 19. Qg4
{ Threatening to play Qg6 with the idea to take on h7 and then White is checkmating with Nf6! }
19... Ne7 20. Ng3
{ The Knight has done its job on the Kingside. Now it's time to get it to a more central square. Notice that White is also threatening Qh5. }
20... h6 21. Ne4 { Such a beautiful Knight on e4! } 21... Ng8
{ A bit passive, but Black was concerned about his King.   21...Nd5  Was more active but could have been met by:  22.Bc1↑  Keeping the b2-pawn defended in case of ...Qb6+. White can continue with the prophylactic Kh1 followed by Rg3, and Bxh6 suddenly becomes a huge threat. }
22. Kh1 { Preparing to get the Rook to the g-file and push g4 eventually. }
22... Rc7 23. Qf3 { Making room for g4. } 23... c5
{ Threatening to push ...c4! } 24. b3 b5 25. g4
{ Our play on the Kingside is much more threatening than Black's ...c4 business. }
25... c4 26. dxc4
{ Here, White played a bit inaccurate. It was better to focus on the Kingside, but he wanted to activate the Rook with Rd1 which makes a lot of sense from a human point of view. The engine would have just gone for the throat with  26.g5!  This was best according to the machine, and it has a cute point.  26...fxg5  27.Nxg5  First of all, the Knight is reaching the e6-square.  27...Qc8  28.Ne6  Rf7  And now White has a very clean transition:  29.bxc4!  bxc4  30.d4+-  And Black is either losing the e-pawn or he is activating our Bishop after ...exd4 Bxd4! }
26... bxc4 27. Rd1 { Activating the Rook with tempo, natural play by White. }
27... Qe8 28. g5 fxg5 29. Bxg5
{ White is trying to break Black's fortress with f6, which turned out to be decisive in the game.   29.Nxg5  Taking with the Knight was still okay, but the Knight does not come with such deadly effect on e6 now, and Black can consolidate with:  29...cxb3  30.cxb3  Rac8  31.Ne6  Rf7∞  And I don't see a way to break Black's position. }
29... cxb3 30. cxb3
{ Keeping it simple.   30.axb3!?  Would have been a nice bait because:  30...Rxc2  Gives White a nice attack after:  31.f6→  And Black's King is in trouble. }
30... Rac8 31. Rg1 Rf7
{ And this is the decisive mistake. Black thought he can stop f6, but it only made it stronger!   31...Qc6!  This was the only move to keep Black in the game, pinning the e4-Knight and preparing to play ...Rf7!  32.f6  Nxf6  33.Bxf6  gxf6  34.Qf5  Bg7∞  Optically I like White, but there might be no way to make real progress. }
32. Qg2 { Threatening Bxh6 with a mate on the g8-square. } 32... Be7
{ Clearing the 8th rank, but allowing: } 33. f6
{ And Black had to resign because of the upcoming checkmate on the h-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "So, Wesley vs. Mamikonian, Tigran"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ Keep in mind that our move order is to start with  2.Nc3  , but we will transpose shortly to the position of interest. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3
{ And we are back to the main tabia of the Vienna. Now Black has a choice between several main moves:  •  4...Bc5   •  4...Bb4   •  4...Na5 }
4... Na5 5. Qf3
{ 5.Bb3  is an alternative, but our main focus is to get the arising structure after ...Nxc4 dxc4 because White has easier play. }
5... Nxc4 6. dxc4
{ This is the pawn structure that we are looking for. Objectively speaking, the position is balanced, but I feel like White has much easier play, and this is also what Jan Gustafsson says in his Lifetime Repertoire. Explaining why he is not a huge fan of the 4... Na5 variation for Black. }
6... d6 7. h3
{ This move is not mandatory, playing  7.Nge2  is completely fine. But you can mix up the move order because h3 is a useful move in this structure anyways. In the theory chapter, I explain why we shall not be afraid of ...Bg4 because White has Qd3 and then we can kick the Bishop "winning half a tempo". }
7... Be7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O c6
{ This is a popular way for Black of treating this structure, creating a square for the Queen on c7, but we are quite happy to see it because the d6-pawn becomes a target now. }
10. Rd1
{ Keeping an eye on the backward pawn. Now White's typical set-up is to play b3-a4 followed by Ba3 with unpleasant pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... Be6 11. b3 { Defending the c4-pawn and preparing a4-Ba3. } 11... Qc7 12.
a4 { Preparing Ba3. } 12... Rad8 13. Ng3
{ Wesley starts with this clever move with the idea to meet ...g6 with Bh6! This is why he is not rushing with Ba3 in the first place. }
13... Kh8 14. Nf5
{ Threatening to take on e7 and then the d6-pawn becomes shaky. } 14... Bxf5
15. Qxf5
{ Taking with the pawn on f5 would have been a bad idea because Black is in time with ...d5! Plus, keep in mind that we are playing for the weak d6-pawn! }
15... g6 16. Qf3 Ng8 { Preparing to generate counterplay by pushing ...f5! }
17. Qe3
{ I like this move by Wesley. The point is to sidestep the f-file while gaining a tempo because Qxa7 is now a big threat! }
17... a6 18. Bb2
{ Watching the enemy King on the long diagonal! White can think about f4 ideas from now on. }
18... Qc8 19. Ne2
{ Opening up the Bishop and preparing to get the Knight to d3 from where it supports White's f4-push. }
19... Qe6 20. Nf4
{ Black might have missed this move. Now the Knight is getting to d3 by winning a tempo. This is not changing the position dramatically because even if Black would have played something like ...Nf6 instead of ...Qe6, White can play Nc1, and then the Knight is reaching the d3-square anyways. }
20... Qc8 21. Nd3 { Preparing to push f4. } 21... f6 22. f4 Rfe8
{ Black is trying to stay solid, but his position is way too passive. White has a lot of ways to improve while Black can only sit tight and wait. This is not a good situation to be in, especially against Wesley So! }
23. Rf1 Bf8 24. Qg3 Bg7 25. fxe5 dxe5
{ Pretty much forced because  25...fxe5  would have allowed  26.c5!  and the e5-pawn will drop. }
26. Rf3 { Preparing to double the Rooks. } 26... c5
{ Black is trying to set up a blockade on the Queenside with ...a5 and ...b6, but White is not going to allow it. }
27. a5
{ A strong positional move! White is making sure that Black will not able to defend the c5-pawn with ...b6 }
27... Qc6 { Hitting the e4-pawn. } 28. Re1 Qc7 { Threatening ...Qxa5. } 29. Bc3
{ Now Black is running out of active moves, and we can focus on collecting the c5-pawn with Qf2 on the next move! }
29... Ne7 30. Qf2 Nc6
{ The Knight is trying to reach the d4-square.   30...Rc8  Defending the c5-pawn, but allowing a deadly exchange sacrifice:  31.Rxf6!  Bxf6  32.Qxf6+  Kg8  33.Bxe5+-  And Black has to give up the Queen to prevent getting mated on g7. }
31. Qxc5 { Collecting the free pawn. } 31... Qd7 32. Qf2 Qe7
{ Defending against a potential exchange sacrifice with Rxf6! } 33. h4
{ Threatening to push h5, opening up the h-file for our Rook. } 33... h5 34.
Rf1 Kh7 35. Kh1 { A small useful move, preparing to break with Rg1 and g4! }
35... Nd4 36. Bxd4 Rxd4 37. Nf4
{ A cute little tactic! The Knight is untouchable because the d4-Rook will hang. White is preparing to get his Knight to d5! }
37... Rxe4 38. Nd5 { Now the f6-pawn is doomed. } 38... Qd7 39. Nxf6+ Bxf6 40.
Rxf6 { Threatening to play Rf7+ } 40... Re7 41. Rf7+
{ Offering a winning Rook endgame if Black decides to take twice! } 41... Kh6
42. Rf8 { Threatening to checkmate with Rh8+ followed by Qf8! } 42... Kh7 43.
Qf7+
{ Just a brilliant conversion. Black is no longer able to avoid the endgame. }
43... Rxf7 44. R1xf7+ { Winning back the Queen. } 44... Qxf7 45. Rxf7+
{ Now the b7-pawn hangs. } 45... Kh6 46. Rxb7 Rxh4+ 47. Kg1
{ The h-pawn is less relevant because White has way too many passed pawns on the Queenside. }
47... Rd4 48. c5 Rd5 49. b4
{ Controlling the c5-square, preparing to push c5 without allowing ...Rc5! }
49... Kg5 50. c6 Rd4 51. c7 Rc4 52. b5 { And the a-pawn Queens. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "So, Wesley vs. Adhiban, Baskaran"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ Wesley starts with the Bishop's Opening, but we are going to transpose into our beloved Vienna shortly. Keep in mind that we start by playing  2.Nc3! }
2... Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3
{ And we arrived at the main position of interest. Black has a big choice between  •  4...Bc5   •  4...Bb4   •  4...Na5 }
4... Na5
{ The young ''beast'' decides to go for the Bishop hunt! In case you were not familiar with it, this is Adhiban's nickname, but who am I trying to fool? Everyone checked out the Lifetime Repertoire with 1. b3! }
5. Qf3 d6
{ At this point we deviate a bit from the other game of Wesley against Mamikonian. That game featured the most popular  5...Nxc4  , but Black is not forced to take the Bishop immediately, and some players try to be tricky and delay it for a bit, as explained in great depth in the theory chapter. }
6. h3 Be7 7. Nge2 { Preparing O-O. } 7... O-O 8. O-O c6
{ With the idea to push ...b5 and later on take on b3, this way eliminating the light-squared Bishop and avoiding our favorite pawn structure arising after ...Nxc4 dxc4! }
9. a4
{ I like this move because it's forcing the game in the direction that we want. If you are looking at it with an engine, it's not going to appreciate it any single bit. Some of the engines might even slightly prefer the move 9. Ng3, but here is the catch: We need to direct the game into familiar territory for us, where we understand the plans and the key ideas rather than blindly following the computer's thoughts.   9.Ng3  White probably underestimated Black's plan of pushing ...b5 and probably thought that ...Nxc4 is going to be played nonetheless, so he decided to just play a natural move, thinking that it is all just going to "transpose".  9...b5!  A pretty unpleasant surprise, if you are not familiar with it!  10.Bb3  g6!  Stopping Nf5 ideas.  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Nd1  White was already lacking a constructive plan, suffering from the 9... b5! deviation.  12...Nxb3  13.axb3∞  White was playing without a plan, and Black spotted his chance in the game: Sanchez Jerez,E @@StartBracket@@2257@@EndBracket@@-Liang,A @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2017 }
9... Nxc4 { Forced, otherwise White will manage to save the Bishop with Ba2! }
10. dxc4 Be6 { Threatening ...Bxc4! } 11. b3 Qa5
{ This is where we slightly deviate from Mamikonian's ...Qc7 set-up. Black can go a bit more aggressive like Adhiban played, but the character of the position remains the same.   11...Qc7  This is the alternative square for the Queen.  12.Rd1  And we are back into the So,W @@StartBracket@@2531@@EndBracket@@-Mamikonian,T @@StartBracket@@2257@@EndBracket@@ Yerevan 2007 game that we covered previously. }
12. Rd1 { Activating the Rook. } 12... Rfd8 13. Bd2
{ Threatening to jump on d5 with the Knight. This is where a small Bishop dance starts. It is very complex, and probably Adhiban was a bit confused during the game too, because it looks like Wesley simply starts repeating the moves, but we will come back to that once the maneuver is over.   13.Ba3  Looks ideal, but Black has a lot of play after:  13...a6⇆  And with ...b5 next, Black is doing just fine. }
13... Qc7 14. Be3 { Preparing to play the standard maneuver with Ng3-Nf5. }
14... Qa5
{ Black is trying to harass White by not allowing him to go for the ideal Ng3-Nf5 maneuver by keeping the c3-Knight under pressure. }
15. Bd2 { Threatening Nd5 again. } 15... Qc7 16. Bg5
{ Now that Wesley knows what Adhiban is up to, he is changing the strategy and goes all the way to g5, with the idea to provoke a weakness on the Kingside. In the meantime, the same Ng3-Nf5 is possible. }
16... h6 { And the weakness does come! } 17. Be3 { Threatening Ng3-Nf5. } 17...
Qa5
{ Keeping the c3-Knight under pressure, making it harder for us to get the desired Ng3-Nf5. }
18. Bd2 { Threatening Nd5 once again. } 18... Qc7 19. Bc1
{ Changing the strategy! Now that we managed to get an additional weakness on the Kingside after Black played h6, we can switch to the Ba3/Bb2 plan. Keep in mind that we neet do watch out for Black's ...d5! before going for our typical plan with Ng3-Nf5.   19.Ng3?!  Would be logical but premature because of :  19...d5⇆  And suddenly Black's pieces are working very well together. }
19... Rd7
{ 19...Qa5  I feel like this would have been a more stubborn approach.  20.Bb2!  Defending the c3-Knight with the simple idea to play Ng3-Nf5.   20.Ba3  Would be the ideal square for the Bishop with the idea to play Rd3-Rad1, but Black has a good resource here:  20...a6⇆  And I couldn't find a good way to stop ...b5! I feel like Black should be fine here.  20...Bf8  This is the more passive alternative, but I like White's position after:   20...d5  This is a concrete approach, but Black can go for it if he wants to force the matters.  21.exd5  cxd5  22.cxd5  We are forced to trade in the center, otherwise Black can push his pawns.  22...Nxd5  23.Nxd5  Bxd5  And now I like going:  24.Qg4!  Keeping an eye on the Kingside.  24...Bc6  25.Ng3⩲  With Nf5 ideas, I like White's potential on the Kingside.  21.Ng3⩲  And we can slowly build up the pressure with Nf5 and Rd3-Rad1. }
20. Ng3 { Preparing to jump with the Knight on f5. } 20... Rad8 21. Ba3
{ Stopping Black from pushing ...d5 before jumping on f5 with the Knight! This is the key move to keep everything under control, and we can start squeezing now.   21.Nf5?!  This is the correct idea, but not the good timing!  21...Bxf5  22.Qxf5  d5⇆  And suddenly Black becomes active. }
21... Qa5
{ Black is not giving White an easy game! The Queen is keeping the c3-Knight under pressure and giving us a hard time with getting Nf5 in. Keep in mind that the immediate Nf5 would be met by ...Bxf5, and then Black is ready to strike with ...d5! Therefore we have to defend the c3-Knight at first by playing:   21...d5??  It's simply not working tactically:  22.Bxe7  Threatening to take on d8.  22...Rxe7  23.exd5  And White simply wins a pawn:  23...cxd5  24.cxd5+-  Black is unable to contest the d5-pawn. }
22. Rd3
{ Keeping the c3-Knight well defended and preparing to jump on f5 with the Knight.   22.Nd5!?  I want you to keep in mind that this move is also a typical trick because the e6-Bishop is trapped. The problem here though is that there will be an annoying ...Bxh3 at the end of the line:  22...cxd5  23.cxd5  White is regaining the piece, but Black has a good way to give it back:  23...Bxh3!  Weakening White's King!  24.gxh3  Nh7∞  And Black has good counterplay on the Kingside. }
22... a6
{ Adhiban does the right thing. He is preparing to push ...b5, but his counterplay comes a bit too late, and Wesley finds the most precise reaction: }
23. Nf5 { Threatening Nxe7 and the d6-pawn drops. } 23... Bxf5 24. Qxf5 b5
{ This was well prepared by Adhiban, but White has a strong response: } 25.
axb5 { Opening up the Rook. } 25... axb5 26. cxb5 { Weakening the d5-square. }
26... cxb5 { Threatening to push ...b4! } 27. Ra2
{ This is the brilliant move that changed the game! White is threatening Bxd6 because the a2-Rook is well defended by the c3-Knight, and ...b4 can be met by Bc1. The a2-Rook is not only active, but it's also defending the c2-pawn, which is a huge factor when considering to jump on d5 with the Knight!   27.Bb2  This is playable, but no longer better for White because Black can play:  27...Qc7  And Nd5 is no longer working because the c2-pawn is vulnerable.  28.Nd5??  Qxc2-+  Black is simply winning. }
27... b4 28. Bc1
{ Preparing to play Nd5 under good conditions on the next move, because the c2-pawn is well protected by the a2-Rook.   28.Bb2??  Would be terrible in view of:  28...Qc5-+  And the c2-pawn hangs. }
28... Qb6 29. Nd5 Nxd5 30. Rxd5
{ Suddenly we have a Sicilian type of structure which has gone terribly wrong for Black because White is dominating the key d5-square. }
30... Rc7 31. Qg4 { Threatening Bxh6. } 31... Kh7 32. Qe2
{ Bringing the Queen closer to the center because there is nothing more to do on the Kingside for now. }
32... Rb8 33. Bd2 { Keeping an eye on the b4-pawn. } 33... Qc6 34. Qd3
{ Preparing to push f4. } 34... Bf8 35. f4
{ Preparing to push f5! Keep in mind that ...exf4 can be met by e5+! because the d3-Queen is opening up against the enemy King. }
35... Kg8 36. f5 Be7 37. Kh2
{ Just a solid move, sidestepping the g1-a7 diagonal. } 37... Kh7 38. Rda5
{ Preparing to play R5a4 ➼ attacking the b4-pawn. Notice that the a2-Rook needs to stay there to protect the c2-pawn. }
38... Qb7 39. R5a4 { Threatening Rxb4! } 39... d5
{ A good practical chance, trying to complicate the game by sacrificing two pawns and activating the Bishop. }
40. exd5 e4
{ The point of the previous move, Black has to give up another one to open up the dark-squares. }
41. Qxe4 Bd6+
{ The Bishop is activating, but White can easily shut things down by playing: }
42. Bf4 Re8 { A tricky attempt! } 43. Qd4
{ Wesley correctly rejects Adhiban's offer!   43.Qxe8  Taking the bait would completely turn the tables after:  43...Bxf4+  44.g3  Bxg3+!!  Opening up the white King.  45.Kxg3  Rc3+  46.Kf2  Qxd5∓  And it's suddenly Black who is having all the fun here. }
43... Bc5 44. Qd3 Rd7 45. d6
{ Threatening to play Ra5. Black's idea to go for simplifications is not bad, but he missed Wesley's 49th move! }
45... Qe4 46. Qxe4 Rxe4 47. Bg3 Bxd6
{ This was the idea behind 45...Qe4!? but it clearly shows that Black missed White's trick! Playing 47...h5!? would have still kept drawing chances, but now the endgame becomes difficult for Black after: }
48. Bxd6 Rxd6 49. c4
{ This clearly came as a shocker to Adhiban because ...bxc3 drops the e4-Rook! Now the b4-pawn is in big trouble. }
49... Rd1
{ Adhiban is seeking for active counterplay, but Wesley just plays with computer precision:   49...Rb6  Would have been met by the precise:  50.Ra5+-  With Rb5 on the next move, Black is in deep trouble. }
50. Ra7 { Threatening the deadly Rxf7. } 50... Kg8 51. Ra8+ Kh7 52. Rf8
{ Setting up an unpleasant mating net because the f5-pawn is taking away the escape g6-square. }
52... Re7 53. Raa8 { Threatening to checkmate with Rh8# } 53... g5 54. f6
{ Forcing Black to give up the f7-pawn because Rg8-Rg7 is a massive threat. }
54... Re6 55. Rxf7+ { Now Black's King is weak. } 55... Kg6 56. Rff8 Rd2
{ A clever attempt by Black to double on the second rank and play for the perpetual check, but Wesley sees everything!   56...Rxf6  Taking the pawn was not helping.  57.Rxf6+  Kxf6  58.Rb8+-  And White wins the b-pawn and the game thanks to the two connected passers. }
57. f7 { Not only meant to Queen but seeking to trade one of Black's Rooks. }
57... Ree2 { Had to be tried. } 58. Rg8+
{ Very precise. Black can't avoid the Rook trade now. } 58... Kxf7 59. Raf8+
{ Forcing the King on the e-file. } 59... Ke6 60. Re8+
{ And after the Rook trade Black has no counterplay remaining. } 60... Kd6 61.
Rxe2 Rxe2 62. Rb8
{ And the b-pawn is lost because .. .Rc5 runs into the cute intermezzo with Rb5+! and White is collecting the b4-pawn on the next move. }
62... Kc6 63. Rxb4 Rb2 64. Rb5 Rb1 65. Kg3 Rb2 66. Kf3 Kc7 67. g3 h5 68. h4 g4+
69. Kf4 Rf2+ 70. Kg5 Rf3 71. Kxh5 Rxg3 72. Kg6
{ And Black resigned. Here is a small list with the key moments of the game:  - White played 16. Bg5 ➼ provoking the small weakness on the Kingside with ...h6  - White was watching out carefully for Black's counterplay and went 21. Ba3! before rushing to jump with the Knight on f5  - 27. Ra2!! is just a brilliant way to shut down Black's counterplay on the Queenside  - 35. f4! making progress on the Kingside  - keeping control over the position with 43. Qd4! avoiding Black's tricks  - 49. c4! This is the kind of move that can easily be missed in a practical game  - the final blow with 57. f7! forcing a winning endgame. }
