1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ Wesley starts with the Bishop's Opening, but we are going to transpose to our beloved Vienna shortly. Keep in mind that we start with  2.Nc3! }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d3
{ And we just got to our main position of interest. Now Black has a variety of main lines:  •  4...Bc5   •  4...Bb4   •  4...Na5 }
4... Bc5 5. f4 d6 6. Nf3
{ So far so good, all has been studied, and we now arrive at a crossroads. Black's most popular moves are  •  6...Bg4   •  6...a6   •  6...O-O   •  6...exf4 }
6... a6
{ This is an interesting line for Black, because it defends against one of White's key ideas, which is to hunt the Bishop with Na4! Black now has ...Ba7 to keep the Bishop alive. Therefore we must change the strategy a bit. }
7. Nd5
{ Threatening the concrete fxe5 followed by Bg5 and also preparing to play to push the pawn to c3, controlling the important d4-square. Now Black has a bunch of alternatives. }
7... Be6 8. Nxf6+ { Spoiling Black's pawn structure. } 8... gxf6
{ 8...Qxf6??  Would allow a typical and deadly trick:  9.f5+-  And Black is losing a piece because Bg5 is a deadly threat! }
9. f5
{ Slightly inferior according to the stronger engines, but I like Wesley's approach because we are forcing our favorite pawn structure after dxc4! }
9... Bxc4 10. dxc4 h5
{ This move is logical knowing that Black will castle Queenside, and then he will try to put pressure on the g-file with ...Rg8!? The good news is that we will be castling on the same side and then use the Kingside to our advantage.   10...b5  This is what's bothering our little Stockfish friend, but I think it's just a complex game after:  11.Qe2∞  With chances for both sides. }
11. c3 { Controlling the critical d4-square. } 11... a5
{ Black's idea is to stop us from playing b4, which was indeed a candidate, but not the first thing on our wishlist. }
12. a4 { Fixing the Queenside. } 12... Qe7 13. Qe2
{ Defending the g2-pawn in advance and preparing to castle Queenside with Bd2 and O-O-O. }
13... Qf8 14. Bd2 { With the idea to castle long on the next move. } 14... h4
15. h3
{ This is an interesting and practical decision by Wesley. I would have castled long, with the idea to meet ...h3 with g3!? but then the pawn on h3 is pretty well defended. Wesley's plan is particularly good because it's fixing the weak pawn on h4, which is going to be an easy target thanks to the presence of our dark-squared Bishop, and it is also preparing to maneuver the Knight to g4 by using the h2 square! }
15... Qg7 16. O-O-O O-O-O
{ So far so good, both sides have finished their development without any major complications happening. It's time to assess the position and figure out a plan for White. If we look at King's safety, we can see that nothing dramatic is happening, and we could say that both Kings are relatively safe.   If we look for weak squares, we can see that Black has the weak square on g4, which we could use for our Knight. White has a weak square on g3, but the big difference is that Black can't make use of it. Now speaking about pawn weaknesses, we can notice Black's isolated pawn on h4, which is a bit overextended, while White's weak pawn could be on g2 if Black would be in time to double on the g-file.   So by figuring out what are the weaknesses in the position we can notice that Black is threatening to play ...Rdg8, and then the best thing that we could do to defend the g2-pawn would be to play Rh2 which is by far not the most active square for the Rook. Therefore we need to block the g-file with our Knight: }
17. Nh2 { Heading towards g4, stopping all the counterplay on the Kingside. }
17... Qf8 { Rerouting the Queen to e7. } 18. Kb1 Kb8 19. Ng4
{ The Knight is active on g4 while completely shutting down the Kingside. }
19... Qe7 20. Be1 { Keeping the h4-pawn under pressure. } 20... Rdg8 21. Rd3
{ Wesley wants to make progress on the Kingside by pushing g3! On one hand, this will get rid of Black's weakness, but on the other hand, it will give him the outside passer on the h-file! You have to understand that at this point, there was no way to increase the pressure on the h4-pawn, so it's best to just let it go, and focus on our passed pawn. }
21... Rg7 22. b3 { Defending everything on the Queenside. } 22... Kc8 23. g3
{ The only way to make progress, but good enough! The h-pawn is very dangerous. }
23... hxg3 24. Rxg3 Rgh7 25. Rd3 { Preparing to push h4! } 25... Rg7 26. h4
Rhg8 { Threatening ...Rxg4! } 27. Rg3 { Defending the Knight. } 27... Nb8
{ Black is rerouting the Knight to d7 so that it will defend the f6-pawn. } 28.
h5 { The h-pawn is too fast! } 28... Nd7 29. h6
{ Forcing Black's Rook on a passive position. } 29... Rh7 30. Bd2
{ Defending the h6-pawn and preparing to invade on the g-file. } 30... Qf8 31.
Qg2 Rgh8 32. Rh4 { Preparing to play Nh2 without blocking the Rook on h1! }
32... c6 33. Nh2
{ Preparing to invade on the seventh by using the g7-outpost. } 33... Kc7 34.
Rg7
{ White is simply threatening to play Rhg4 and Rxh7 with the idea to invade with the second Rook after that. }
34... Qb8
{ Black is trying to seek for some counterplay with ...b5 but White keeps a clear head: }
35. Kc2 { Defending the b3-pawn in advance. } 35... b5 36. cxb5 cxb5 37. axb5
Qxb5 38. Qf1
{ Forcing the Queens off and making sure that Black will get no chance for any tricks. }
38... Qxf1 39. Nxf1 Kd8 40. Rhg4
{ Preparing to take on h7 and follow up with Rg8. } 40... Ke7 41. Rxh7 Rxh7 42.
Rg8
{ Black is completely tied down. Wesley decides to win by creating another passer on the Queenside because the h7-Rook is unable to defend that side of the board. }
42... Bf2 43. b4 { Maybe not the most accurate way, but a very human move. }
43... axb4 44. cxb4 d5
{ Black tried to create some counterplay, but the b-pawn will decide the game: }
45. exd5 Nb6 46. Kd3 Nxd5 47. Nh2
{ Preparing to play Ng4, taking good care of the h6-pawn. } 47... Bh4 48. Ng4
Bg5 49. Bxg5 fxg5 50. b5
{ You can see that White is simply winning because the h7-Rook has to guard the outside passer on the h-file. }
50... Kd7 51. Rg7 { Collecting everything. } 51... Rh8 52. Nxe5+ Ke7 53. Ng6+
{ And Black resigned. Here is a small list with the key moments of the game:  - when Black played 8... gxf6  - fixing the weakness on the Kingside with 15. h3!?  - the key maneuver with 17. Nh2!  - the breakthrough with 23. g3  - creating the decisive passer with 43. b4!? }
