[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ White starts the game with a wild move order, but I would like to just kindly remind everyone that we start by playing  2.Nc3!  You can simply skip the first six moves because we will just transpose to one of the main tabias of the Vienna. }
2... Bc5 3. Nf3 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. d3
{ The main tabia of the 4... Bc5 variation. Now Black has a wide choice of playable moves:  •  6...Bg4   •  6...a6   •  6...exf4   •  6...O-O }
6... Bg4 { Black's most popular move. Here White has a typical reaction: } 7.
Na4
{ Hunting the dark-squared Bishop! By eliminating it, we are gaining the Bishop pair, and we will also be able to castle short, which is usually problematic in the ...Bc5 lines. }
7... Bb6 8. Nxb6 axb6 9. c3
{ Controlling the key d4-square and creating a square on c2 for the Bishop. If Black goes ...Na5, we can save the Bishop by playing Bb5+ and then Ba4-Bc2, keeping the Bishop pair alive. }
9... d5
{ Black somehow has to complicate the game. Otherwise, White would have free pressure with the Bishop pair. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. h3 { Forcing Black to give up the Bishop! } 11... Bxf3 12.
Qxf3 { Attacking the d5-Knight. } 12... Nxf4 13. O-O
{ The smartest move order! We are going to take on f4 on the next move, avoiding Black's ...Qe7+ annoying idea. }
13... O-O 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Qxf4 { Threatening Bxf7+ } 15... Qd7 16. d4
{ A useful move, controlling the e5-square. } 16... Rae8 17. Rf3
{ White's play is simple, the idea is to triple on the f-file next move. }
17... Nd8 18. Raf1 Kh8 19. Rg3
{ Threatening to win directly with Rxg7 followed by Qf6+ and Rf5! } 19... f5
{ Black is avoiding the immediate danger, but now the e6-square has been permanently weakened. }
20. Re3 { Moving the action to the e-file! } 20... g6
{ Defending the f5-pawn.   20...Rxe3  It looks like Black can fight for the e-file, but White has a cool trick:  21.Qxe3  Re8  Looks very natural, but it fails to:  22.Rxf5+-  And Black is having back rank problems. }
21. Rfe1 { Threatening to take twice on e8 and then collect the c7-pawn. }
21... Rxe3 22. Rxe3 Nf7 23. Qh4 { Threatening the direct Qf6+ and Re7. } 23...
Kg7 24. Re7 { White's Rook is simply too strong on the seventh. } 24... Qc6 25.
Bb3 { Black is completely tied down. } 25... Qd6 26. Re6
{ Forcing a winning endgame because Qf6 is a deadly threat. } 26... Qd8 27.
Qxd8 Nxd8
{ 27...Rxd8  Is the same as resigning because White has a winning pawn endgame after:  28.Re7  Rf8  29.Rxc7  Kf6  30.Rxb7+-  Trading everything on f7 is also completely winning, but why not collect all the pawns? }
28. Re7+ Kf6 29. Rxc7 { Threatening Rxh7. } 29... h5 30. Rd7
{ With Rd6 being an unstoppable threat, White is completely winning. } 30... h4
31. Rd6+ Kg5 32. Rxb6 Re8 { Threatening to activate with ...Re2! } 33. Rd6
{ Keeping an eye on the d8-Knight. } 33... Nc6 34. Kf2
{ Controlling all the entry squares! Black's position is just dead lost. }
34... Re7 35. Re6 Rxe6 36. Bxe6 Kf4 37. Bd5 { And Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ponkratov, Pavel vs. Stambulian, Arsen"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ I know you must be shocked, but we do have a game starting with our move order! }
2... Nf6 3. f4
{ 3.Bc4  Could transpose to the main tabia of the Vienna after  3...Nc6  and  4.d3   but you have to keep in mind that Black has a serious alternative of going  3.Bc4  Nxe4  , which is the main reason why we are going for the Vienna Gambit instead! }
3... d5
{ The main move, and Black's only respectable try. We will quickly go through the following seven moves because everything is explained in great depth in the theory chapter. We will notice the moment when Pavel deviates from our main recommendation. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be6 7. Bf4 Nd7 8. O-O-O c6 9. Ne2 Qa5
{ And we arrived at one of the key positions for the ...Be6 and ...Nd7 set-up. Black is threatening to play ...Qxa2, and we have to do something about it. Pavel deviates from our main move by playing the natural: }
10. a3
{ Pavel takes care of the a2-pawn in a different way, but the character of the position remains the same, and the game is still very instructive for our topic.   10.Kb1!  This is what we are focusing on in the theory chapter because we are not afraid of:  10...d4  Threatening ...Qxa2!  11.a3!  After this simple move, White is just better.  11...dxc3  12.Nxc3⩲  And White has the upper hand in this type of position. For more details, check out the theory chapter. }
10... Nc5
{ Black is protecting the e6-Bishop @@StartBracket@@anticipating Nd4@@EndBracket@@, and he also has ...Ne4 ideas in some positions. For the time being, b4 is not bothering Black since the a3-pawn will hang with check, but it turns out that Pavel had a deeper understanding: }
11. Nd4 Be7 { Preparing O-O. } 12. c4
{ This is a common motif if you studied the theory chapter carefully. The point is that ...dxc4 runs into Nxe6 followed by Bxc4 and White's Bishop pair starts to shine. Additionally to what we normally see in the theory chapter, White has a concrete threat of winning a piece with b4. The f3-Queen defends the a3-pawn, which Black must have missed in the first place! }
12... Qa4
{ Sidestepping b4 and threatening ...dxc4!   12...dxc4  Gives White the typical initiative after:  13.Nxe6!  The key intermezzo!  13...Nxe6  14.Bxc4  Suddenly, Black is dealing with a very unpleasant threat of Bxe6 followed by Qb3! hitting both the b7 and the e6 pawn.  14...O-O  It's also not solving all the issues because White is just in time with:   14...Nxf4  Looks normal, but loses the f7-pawn.  15.Qxf4  15...O-O  16.Rhf1±  And White will collect the f7-pawn next with a close to winning position.  15.Rd7±  And the Rook is very annoying on the seventh rank! }
13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5
{ You don't see a Queen sac this early in the game every day! In reality, it's just a Queen trade, but it looks very aesthetic, and it's objectively the best move! }
14... cxd5 15. Bb5+ { Winning back the Queen. } 15... Qxb5 16. Nxb5
{ But all of a sudden, Black has to answer a bunch of unpleasant questions. }
16... Ne6 17. Be3 { The d-pawn is simply lost. } 17... a6 18. Nc3
{ Threatening Nxd5. } 18... d4
{ Black is finding some nice resources because if the Knight was landing on d5, that would have been unpleasant. }
19. Bxd4 Bg5+ { Not forced, but I guess Black had some ...Bf4 ideas in mind. }
20. Kb1 Rd8 21. Ne4
{ For sure, this was missed by Black when he went 19... Bg5+, but Pavel finds the best move!   21.Bf2  I guess this was what Black expected, and the game is pretty unclear after:  21...Bf4∞  And to me, it looks like the e5-pawn could be vulnerable, even though the computer is not impressed. }
21... Rxd4
{ 21...Nxd4  Was probably slightly better than the game.  22.Nxg5  O-O  23.Rhe1±  But White's advantage is still healthy. }
22. Rxd4 Nxd4 23. Nxg5
{ White has a technically winning position, but there is still a lot of work to be done. It's impressive how Pavel is converting this endgame. }
23... h6 24. Ne4 { The Knight is heading to d6 or c5. } 24... Ke7
{ The King is useful in the center. } 25. Nc5
{ Winning a pawn on the Queenside because ...Rb8 runs into Rd1 and Rd7!   25.Rd1+-  Was a bit more precise, activating the Rook first. }
25... Rc8
{ Black is trying to create counterplay on the c-file, but this allowed White to go for the Rook endgame: }
26. Nxb7 Rxc2 27. Rd1 { Now Black is forced to go after the b7-Knight. } 27...
Rc7 28. Rxd4 Rxb7
{ We are approaching a new phase of the game, where Black managed to trade a pair of Knights. Generally, I would think that his drawing chances have improved because when you are down a pawn, the best drawing chances are given by the opposite coloured Bishops endgames and the Rook endgames. Now that I saw how the game went, it's hard to say, Pavel's technique was just  impressive! }
29. Rd6 a5 30. Rd5 Ra7 31. a4 { Fixing the weak pawn. } 31... Ke6 32. Rb5 Kf5
{ Now Black tries his luck with the King walk, but White's pawns are just faster in this race. Pavel simply marches his King to b6! }
33. Kc2 { The King is heading towards b6. } 33... Ke4 34. Kc3 Ke3 35. Kc4 Kf2
36. g4 { Slowing down Black's enthusiasm on the Kingside a bit. } 36... Kg2 37.
Kc5 { Preparing to play Kb6 and win the a-pawn. } 37... Kxh2 38. Kb6 Ra8 39.
Kb7 { The white King is just a monster! } 39... Re8 40. Rxa5
{ From now on it should be a relatively easy win, but we will have another interesting moment. }
40... Kg3 41. Rc5 { Preparing to push the a-pawn down the board. } 41... Kxg4
42. a5 Re7+ 43. Kb6 Re6+ 44. Rc6
{ Giving Black a small bait on e5, but the position is winning nonetheless. }
44... Re8
{ 44...Rxe5  Was leading to a similar scenario to the game.  45.a6  Re8  46.a7  h5  47.Kb7  h4  48.a8=Q  Rxa8  49.Kxa8  h3  50.b4+-  We are going to Queen the b-pawn and sacrifice the Rook for the h-pawn. }
45. a6 h5 46. a7 h4 47. Kb7 h3 48. a8=Q Rxa8 49. Kxa8
{ Now it looks almost resignable at first because White can sac the Rook for the h-pawn and Queen the b-pawn, but an interesting situation is arising: }
49... h2 50. Rc1 Kf3 51. b4 g5 { The only practical chance. } 52. Rh1
{ The most practical way.   52.b5  This is the cold-blooded win preferred by the engine, but let's go a bit deeper.  52...g4  53.b6  g3  54.b7  g2  55.b8=Q  g1=Q  56.Qb7++-  And somehow White is creating a mating construction. Now think about this, you've been probably playing for five hours at least, and the game depends on a long sequence of precise moves @@StartBracket@@around 8 moves@@EndBracket@@. I mean, Magnus is good at those, but this is a tricky situation. Yes, sometimes it's the only way to win, and you have to go for it, but in this case, Pavel finds the best practical approach, which gives White the win 100% without having to calculate crazy lines! }
52... Kg2 53. Rxh2+ { And Black resigned because: } 53... Kxh2 54. e6
{ This was Pavel's intention for sure. } 54... fxe6 55. b5 g4 56. b6 g3 57. b7
g2 58. b8=Q+
{ And White has a book-winning endgame. Now compare this to 52. b5, White had to find 54. e6! which is a two moves sequence instead of calculating 8 precise moves @@StartBracket@@actually maybe even more@@EndBracket@@. Chess is a practical game where you should try to make your life easier all the time! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Perunovic, Milos vs. Kalezic, Blazo"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ Black goes for the Modern Variation. The only thing that you need to remember is to simply let the pawn go, and play  3.d4!  Make sure to check out the theory chapter for more details on this opening. }
3. Nf3
{ This could be a viable alternative to  3.d4  , but I just feel like it's a bit less flexible. Anyways, the opening moves are pretty standard, and we can focus on the typical plans and ideas once both sides finish development. For more details about the opening, you can check out the theory chapter. }
3... Nxd5 4. d4 Bg4 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This is our main position of interest which can be reached from many move orders. }
6... e6 7. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 7... Be7 8. h3
{ Forcing the Bishop to show its path. } 8... Bh5 9. O-O c6 10. Bf4
{ Developing the Bishop on the most active square. } 10... O-O 11. Qd2
{ White is going for the standard development with Rfd1-Rac1. } 11... Nbd7 12.
Rfd1 Nb6
{ Black has a tactical trick in mind, but the Knight ends up being misplaced on b6. We have to watch out for ...Bxf3 and ...Nxc4! }
13. Qe3
{ We are ready to recapture on f3 with the Queen, keeping a healthy pawn structure. }
13... Re8 14. Rac1 a5 15. Bf1
{ Improving the position little by little. We are going to push g4 on the next move. }
15... a4 16. g4
{ Breaking the pin so that we can jump on e5 with the Knight. This move might look risky to the newer players, but because we have so much space we can afford such moves to make progress. }
16... Bg6 17. Ne5
{ Threatening the  unpleasant h4-h5, which is putting the g6-Bishop under a big question mark. }
17... a3
{ Trying to make a mess on the Queenside, but we can keep everything solid with: }
18. b3 { Keeping a nice and sound pawn structure. } 18... Nfd7 19. Bg2
{ Threatening to open up the position with d5. } 19... Nxe5 20. dxe5
{ Attacking the Queen and creating an outpost on d6. } 20... Nd7
{ 20...Qc7  21.h4!  Threatening to push h5!  21...h6   21...Bxh4?  Would fail because of:  22.g5+-  And the Bishop gets trapped on h4.  22.h5  Bh7  23.Be4!  Trading the Bishops so we can play Ne4 without allowing Black to eliminate it!  23...Bxe4  24.Nxe4↑  With promising chances on the Kingside. }
21. Ne4 { Threatening to occupy the outpost with Nd6! } 21... Qc7
{ 21...Bxe4  I think this was a bit better for Black, but White is still in good shape after:  22.Bxe4  Threatening to expand with c5-b4. There is also a small tactical trick with Bxh7+ followed by Qd3 ➼ picking up the d7-Knight, but it might be even better to just go for the positional squeeze.  22...Bc5  23.Qc3  Qe7  This is a good try to control the dark-squares, but we can take the bull by the horns and play:  24.b4±  And White is much better because ...Bxb4 runs into Rxd7! }
22. Nd6 Red8
{ 22...Bxd6  Can be met by:  23.Rxd6±  And we can slowly build up the pressure on the Queenside. Meanwhile, look how out of play the Bishop on g6 is. Simply hitting the desert as we like to say! }
23. c5 { Preparing b4-b5. White is just crushing. } 23... Nb8 24. b4
{ With the idea to push b5. } 24... Na6 25. Qb3
{ Keeping the enemy Knight out of the game!   25.b5?!  Would allow unnecessary counterplay after:  25...Nb4∞  And the Knight reaches the d5-square for absolutely no reason! }
25... Qb8 26. b5 { Finally breaking through. Black is just lost. } 26... Nc7
27. bxc6
{ Still good, but White had a better move.   27.Nxb7!  Was the cleanest, and the pawns are just too strong.  27...Qxb7  28.Bxc6  Qb8  29.Rxd8+  Bxd8  30.b6!  We can simply ignore the Rook.  30...Nd5  31.Bxd5!  exd5  32.b7  Ra7  33.c6  Threatening c7.  33...Bc7  34.e6+-  I find this line very cute because ...Bxf4 is simply lost after c7! and White is Queening. }
27... bxc6 28. Bxc6 { Going for the easy pawn grab. } 28... Qxb3 29. axb3 a2
{ 29...Rab8  Was another try, but White wins after the very precise:  30.Bd2!  Preparing b4 and Ba5 ideas.  30...Rxb3  31.Ba5+-  And White wins. }
30. Bxa8 Rxa8 31. b4 { The connected passers are way too strong to handle. }
31... f6 32. b5 Nd5 33. b6
{ Black can have the Bishop, we are going to get a new Queen. } 33... Nxf4 34.
b7 Rf8 35. Ra1 { Getting rid of the only possible source of counterplay. }
35... Nxh3+ 36. Kf1 Bb1 37. Rdxb1
{ When we are so much ahead, this move comes very natural. The material is simply irrelevant when you have two pawns that are about to Queen. }
37... axb1=Q+ 38. Rxb1 Rb8 39. c6 { Threatening c7. } 39... Bd8 40. Ra1
{ And Black resigned, because there is no way to deal with the Ra8 followed by Nb5 threat, and the pawns are Queening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alekseev, Evgeny V vs. Fier, Alexandr"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4
{ Alekseev's pet line. He used it successfully on several occasions. This game is very relevant for the theoretical state of the line because Black goes for the most aggressive line with  3...Nc6  and  4.--  Bg4! }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Nc3
{ The key move for the 3. d4!? move order. Going  5.Be2  is fine, but it makes much more sense to start with 3. Nf3 if you are looking for that position. }
5... Qh5
{ The main move.  5...Qa5  or  5...Qf5  are two alternatives for Black that were covered in the theory chapter. }
6. Bb5 Bxf3
{ Black could also try  6...O-O-O  or  6...e6!?  . For more details, make sure to check out the theory chapter. }
7. Qxf3 Qxf3 8. gxf3 e6
{ Threatening to play ...Nge7 and maintain a healthy pawn structure. } 9. Bxc6+
{ We need to double Black's pawns on the Queenside to hope for anything. } 9...
bxc6
{ This is a typical endgame for the 3. d4 variation. I think it's really easy to underestimate White's play because generally, you tend to feel pretty safe without the Queens on the board in this structure as Black. Strategically speaking, Black's position is a bit risky because White can expand with the pawns on the Queenside, and use the g-file for the Rook, which gives him a little bit of pressure. Let's see how Alekseev proceeds: }
10. Ne4 { Activating the Knight and preparing to defend the d4-pawn with c3. }
10... O-O-O 11. c3 Nf6 12. Bg5
{ This pin is  annoying for Black. Suddenly White has a small but steady edge. }
12... Be7 13. Rg1 { With ideas to invade on the seventh after Bxf6 and Rg7!? }
13... Rhg8 14. Ke2 { The King is useful in the center! } 14... h6 15. Nxf6
{ Forcing a very nice Rook endgame. } 15... Bxf6
{ Forced because  15...gxf6  allows  16.Bxh6 } 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rg3
{ Threatening to win the g-file with Rag1! } 17... Rg6 18. Rag1
{ We improved the situation at max on the Kingside. Now we are going to start pushing on the other side of the board. }
18... Rdg8 19. Kd3 { Bringing the King to c4. } 19... Kd7 20. Kc4
{ Preparing to push on the Queenside with b4-a4-a5! } 20... Kd6 21. b4 f5
{ With ...f4 in mind, fighting for the g-file. } 22. f4
{ Avoiding the complications! } 22... Rg4 23. h3
{ Forcing Black to either stay passive or enter a losing King and pawn endgame. }
23... Rxg3 24. Rxg3 Rxg3
{ Hard to criticize Black for his decision, but White is simply winning!   24...Ra8  Was a tough move to make, but probably not changing the result.  25.Rg7  Ke7  26.a4  Threatening to push a5 and Kc5.  26...a5  Threatening ...axb4 Kxb4 and ...Rb8+! ➼ activating the Rook.  27.Kb3!  axb4  28.cxb4+-  The point! Not allowing the enemy Rook to activate. }
25. fxg3
{ White is simply winning because he will break with g4 and then bring the King to h5. It's simply shocking to me that White can win in this fashion without Black making any obvious mistakes. This is one of the main reasons why this 3. d4 line caught my attention. Just watch how a 2600 Grandmaster is defenceless against it. }
25... f6 26. Kd3 { Preparing to push c4. } 26... h5
{ Black has to try this move, but g4 will come anyways once the King arrives on f3. }
27. c4 Kd7 28. a4
{ It is hard to criticize White for making this natural move. Now Black has a shocking drawing mechanism.   28.Ke3!  Going for the g4-break was the smooth way to win.  28...Ke7  29.Kf3  Kf7  30.a4!  We are going to fix the Queenside first with b5. Notice that Black can no longer use the ...a5 trick.  30...Kg7  31.b5  cxb5  32.axb5  The Queenside is fixed. We are ready to break with g4 next.  32...Kf7  33.g4  hxg4+  34.hxg4  fxg4+  35.Kxg4  Kg6  And at first it seems that Black manages some sort of blockade, but White has a typical breakthrough:  36.f5+!  We are going to win back the pawn, with a more active King!  36...exf5+  37.Kf4  Black is in zugzwang.  37...Kg7  38.Kxf5  Kf7  39.d5  Ke7  40.c5+-  No counterplay. Black is either giving up the f6-pawn or we Queen.  40...Kf7  41.d6!  cxd6  42.b6+-  And White Queens. }
28... Kd6
{ Missing the chance. Now White is back on the right track:   28...a5!!  This shocking move was probably not even considered. The idea is to sacrifice another pawn with ...c5, and then Black gets counterplay based on the protected passer with ...e5!  29.bxa5  c5!!  Simply shocking. Black is giving up two pawns to save the King and pawn endgame. In 99% of the cases, being up a pawn is equal to a win in King and pawn endgames, but thanks to Black's connected passer, the game is drawn.  30.dxc5  Kc8!  Only move.  31.c6  Kb8  32.Kd4  Ka7  33.Kc5  Ka6  34.Kb4  e5=  And Black has enough play to draw. }
29. Ke3 { Going for the right plan to break with g4. } 29... Kd7 30. Kf3 Ke7
31. g4 fxg4+ 32. hxg4 hxg4+ 33. Kxg4 Kd6
{ Black knew that passive defence will give White a free win, so he tries to make counterplay by meeting the outflanking with  34.Kh5  by playing  ...e5!  drawing on the spot. }
34. Kf3
{ Very cold-blooded. White is not rushing it and avoids Black's trick.   34.Kh5?  e5!  Was Black's idea.  35.dxe5+  fxe5  36.f5  e4=  And both sides will Queen. }
34... Ke7
{ 34...e5  Was no longer working:  35.dxe5+  fxe5  36.f5!  And Black will run out of moves soon:  36...Ke7  37.Ke4  37...Kf6  38.c5  a6  39.a5+-  And Black is facing a zugzwang situation. }
35. Ke4 { We are going to break with f5! } 35... Kd6 36. f5 Ke7 37. b5
{ Fixing the Queenside. } 37... cxb5 38. axb5 exf5+
{ Black could no longer stay passive, so he tries to create a passer.   38...Kd7  Would result in a slow, but sure death after:  39.c5  Ke7  40.fxe6  Kxe6  41.d5+!  Ke7  42.Kf5+-  And Black has to give up the f6-pawn or White Queens. In both cases, White is winning. }
39. Kxf5 c6 { A good try, but not changing the outcome of the game. } 40. bxc6
a5 41. c5 a4 42. d5 a3
{ Black's pawn is pretty fast, but White is usually either mating with the pawns or creating a Queen with check in this type of scenario. }
43. d6+ Kd8 44. Ke6 a2 45. c7+ Kc8 46. d7+ Kxc7 47. Ke7 a1=Q
{ Black Queens first, but we are going to Queen with check! } 48. d8=Q+ Kc6 49.
Qb6+ Kd5 50. Qd6+ Kc4 51. c6
{ Black is simply lost in the Queen endgame because the c-pawn is unstoppable. }
51... f5 52. c7 Qg7+ 53. Kd8 Qg8+ 54. Kd7 Qf7+ 55. Kc6 Qe8+ 56. Kb7
{ We can meet ...Qb5+ with Qb6, so Black so nothing better than to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kotronias, Vasilios vs. Short, Nigel D"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ I've picked this game because it's really interesting to see how Nigel Short, one of the greatest chess players of all time, handles the Four Pawns Attack. Of course, Nigel is famous for his French Defense, but he used to implement the Alekhine as a surprise weapon on several occasions. }
2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4
{ The first crossroads of the game. Black can choose from  •  5...dxe5   •  5...g6   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g5!? }
5... dxe5
{ Black goes for the main move. Make sure to check out the theory chapter where I cover the alternatives in great depth! }
6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3
{ The precise way to defend the d4-pawn!   7.Nf3?  Would already be a big inaccuracy because Black gets a dream version after:  7...Bg4⇆  And White's center is fragile. }
7... Bf5
{ This move has to be played because going for the direct ...e6 would permanently close the light-squared Bishop, putting Black in a painful position. }
8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3
{ Now Black can choose from two main plans:  •  9...Qd7  followed by  10.--  O-O-O   •  9...Be7  followed by  10.--  O-O  @@StartBracket@@this one is featured in the next game@@EndBracket@@ }
9... Qd7
{ Nigel goes for the most aggressive plan. The good news is that White has a great way to counter this approach. }
10. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 10... O-O-O 11. O-O f6
{ 11...Bg4  Is a bit more popular here, but it's still good for White after:  12.c5⩲  As explained in the theory chapter in greater depth. }
12. d5 { This move is putting Black's set-up under a big question mark! } 12...
Nxe5 13. Nxe5 fxe5 14. a4
{ Black is suddenly facing a very unpleasant threat of a5! Notice that ...exd5 would drastically fail after Rxf5! and Black is unable to take the Rook because Bg4 wins the Queen. }
14... a5 15. Nb5 { Threatening the simple Qe1-Qf2. } 15... Bb4 16. d6
{ Black is simply making his best just to survive. } 16... Na8
{ Had to be played sadly... } 17. c5 Kb8
{ 17...c6  18.Na3+-  With Nc2 next, White is just winning. } 18. Bf3
{ Activating the Bishop. } 18... c6 19. Na3
{ Threatening to play Nc2 followed by Nxb4. } 19... e4 20. Be2 b6
{ Black had to try this as otherwise the Knight will remain on a8. } 21. cxb6
Qxd6 22. Qxd6+
{ Not the most precise move, but still much better.   22.Qb3+-  Was probably leading to a faster win for White. }
22... Rxd6
{ 22...Bxd6  Was not improving Black's situation after:  23.Nc4  Bb4  24.g4!  Bg6  25.Ne5+-  And the threat of Nxc6 is decisive.  25...Kb7  Runs into:  26.Nxg6  hxg6  27.Rf7+  And the Rook is activating with tempo.  27...Kb8  28.Ba6+-  With Rb7 on the next move, White is completely winning. }
23. Rad1
{ Very natural.   23.Bf4?  Going for the exchange would be naive here because it allows Black's Knight back in the game:  23...Nxb6  24.Bxd6+  Bxd6∞  With ...Nd5 coming, Black is not worse at all!   23.Ba6!  Was the most precise according to the engine. White is threatening to play Nc4 followed by Bf4 with a mating net.  23...Nxb6  24.Bxb6  c5  The only defensive try, but White just wins after:  25.Nc4+-  And White manages to keep up the extra material. }
23... Rhd8
{ 23...Rxd1  24.Rxd1  e5  Could have been a better defensive try.  25.Nc2  25...Be7  And now White has to find a precise sequence in order to be better:  26.b4!  axb4  27.Bc4±  The key move, not allowing ...Be6! White is just winning with the connected passers.   27.a5?  Gives Black a lot of play after:  27...Be6∞  And ...b3 turns out to be really annoying. }
24. Rxd6 Rxd6 25. g4 { Now Black is in concrete trouble. } 25... Bd2
{ Trying to complicate the matters, but White finds the cold blooded:   25...Bg6  Allows a direct win after:  26.Rf8+  Kb7  27.Ba6+  Deflecting the King.  27...Kxa6  28.Rxa8+  Kb7  29.Ra7+  Kb8  30.Nc4+-  With Bf4 next, White just Queens. }
26. Bf2 { Heading towards g3! } 26... Kb7 27. Nc4
{ Now everything is hanging. } 27... Rd5 28. gxf5 exf5 29. Rd1
{ White is simply up a piece in the endgame. } 29... Bb4 30. Be3 g6 31. Kf2
Rxd1 32. Bxd1 c5 33. Bb3 Nxb6 34. Nxb6 Kxb6 35. Bg8
{ Black resigned because White is about to collect a bunch of pawns after Bh7. }
