[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Xiong, Jeffery vs. Bortnyk, Olexandr"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ I've picked this game because first of all, it is a very well-played game by White, and second of all, on the Black side we have Olexandr Bortnyk, who is by far the biggest specialist of the Alekhine in our days. Yes, he mostly uses the Alekhine in rapid games, but it doesn't make his success with the opening any less impressive! }
2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4
{ 4.a4  a5  5.Ra3!?  Could lead to a fun game, but Black should have enough defensive resources. }
4... d6 5. f4
{ The starting position for the Four Pawns Attack, and the first crossroads for Black. The alternatives are:  •  5...dxe5   •  5...Bf5   •  5...g6   •  5...g5!? }
5... Bf5 6. Nc3 e6 7. Nf3 dxe5 8. fxe5 Be7
{ Playing for a short castle. This is Black's safest plan.   8...Nc6  9.Be3  Qd7  Was seen in the other model game between Kotronias and Short. }
9. Be3 O-O 10. Be2 f6
{ This is the only way to generate some counterplay for Black, but at the same time it's also creating a weakness on e6. }
11. exf6 Bxf6 12. O-O Nc6 13. b3 { Keeping the c4 pawn well defended. } 13...
Qe7 14. Bd3
{ I really love this idea. If Black does nothing, White will simply play Ne4, hunting the enemy dark-squared Bishop. }
14... Bg4 15. Be4
{ We are going to eliminate the c6-Knight, which is putting pressure on the d4-pawn. }
15... Rad8 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Ne4 { We are going to play Nxf6 next. } 17... e5
{ Black tries to generate some play in the center, but White has it all under control. }
18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. h3 Bxf3
{ 19...Bh5  Would lead to something similar after:  20.Qe1  Introducing Qg3 ideas and threatening dxe5.  20...Bxf3  Can simply be met by:  21.Qg3+!  Kh8  22.Qxf3  exd4  23.Bh6+-  We are going to collect the c6-pawn next, with a very similar position to the game. }
20. Qxf3 exd4
{ Black takes the d4-pawn, but we are going to collect the c6-pawn shortly. }
21. Bh6
{ First of all, we are making sure that the Bishop is safe, and then we can collect on c6. }
21... Rf7 22. Qxc6
{ 22.Rae1+-  Would have been more precise, but it's hard to criticize White for playing such a natural move. }
22... d3 23. Rad1 { Preparing to collect the d3-pawn with Rf3/ Qf3 ideas. }
23... f5
{ Black has a trick! The point is to play ...Rd6 next, which could win a piece if you are not careful, so for this reason White played: }
24. Qf3
{ Sidestepping Black's trick with ...Rd6 and threatening to collect the d3-pawn. }
24... Qe4 25. Qg3+ Kh8 26. Rfe1 { Getting rid of the annoying Queen! } 26...
Qd4+ 27. Be3 Qf6 28. Bf4 { Once the Bishop arrives on e5 it is game over! }
28... Nd7 { Stopping White from playing Be5, but allowing the simple: } 29.
Rxd3 { And White is simply up a pawn with a much better position. } 29... Rg8
30. Qe3 Rfg7 31. Re2 Qa1+ 32. Kh2 Qf1 33. Rdd2
{ White is making sure to protect the g2-pawn, which is the only source of counterplay for Black, and then he can start collecting the rest of the Queenside. Notice that Rf2! is a threat in the current position. }
33... Nf6 34. Be5
{ Killing all the potential counterplay. Black has problems on the a1-e5 diagonal. }
34... Rg6 35. Qc3 Kg7 36. Rf2 Qe1 37. Rd7+ { Oh no, my Queen! } 37... Kh6 38.
Bf4+ Kh5 39. Rxh7+ { Not necessary, but cute. } 39... Nxh7 40. Qxe1
{ And Black has to stop the clock and resign @@StartBracket@@not literally because it was an online game@@EndBracket@@. }
